animal.description:
Nellie is a dog that needs a firm but understanding owner that will be patient with her and help her understand she is finally home but she is the dog not the master. Nellie must be the only animal in the home, she does not like other dogs or cats. At the shelter, she minds her own business and doesn't instigate with other dogs so if you have a fenced in yard to keep her away from other dogs and cats, she'll be fine in your neighborhood, but if approached by other animals, she will assert her dominance. 



Nellie cannot go to an active home that have people coming and going, and she cannot go with children. Nellie would do best with a single owner who respects that she needs to be put up when visitors come to the home as she can get protective of her person. Due to her vocalization and special needs, she needs a home with a fenced yard, no apartment living for her. 



Nellie will not be a fit for most families; however, we know her perfect owner is out there. Nellie does great at the shelter with structure and guidance and a set routine. Nellie needs an owner who will provide stability and routine for her to help her feel safe and secure.

animal.description:
Update - Boss is now in foster, get your app in today to meet this great boy!!

Boss continually gets overlooked and we aren't sure why. He did have some trouble decompressing when he first arrived at TAPS . Since he has settled in, he seems great. He does have some sensitive areas where he might give out a little warning growl if you touch him in the wrong place but that is due to carry over from a rough life. It appears he had a collar embedded in his neck at one point. 

While he can act a little grouchy in his kennels when other dogs walk by, we have done a dog intro with him and he actually did very well. 

We do suggest a quieter, adult only home for Boss because we think he still carries scars from his past but give this baby a chance to trust and you'll have a friend for life. He may also need some guidance on re-potty training but a few gentle reminders should set him on the potty training path. He does not like to be handled around the neck, we believe this is from his past and his embedded collar but he seems fine being handled everywhere else.

animal.description:
Lois Lane is looking for her next Clark Kent! Could you be the one to save her?

Lois Lane is a 4.5 y/o pocket pittie/terrier mix. We believe she would do best in an active household with a big fenced yard. She is a staff and volunteer favorite because her spunky attitude and zest for life brings a laugh and a smile to everyone's face. We discovered over the summer that she absolutely LOVES swimming so would love to see her go to a home where she can have access to a pool. 

Her adventurous personality has led her over fences and through kennels and crates, so we are hoping she can go to a home with a tall fence or with someone who is committed to keeping her on a long tie out while she is inside the fenced yard! She has a wonderful, active personality and we believe she would do best in an adult-only home and with a very active adoptive family. 

Apply for her at www.tapsshelter.org!

UPDATE: Lois Lane is a 5-1/2 year-old, 44-pound, female, low-rider pit bull mix who came to TAPS one year ago and although she came with no information, we have learned so much about her during her stay at TAPS. Lois' story started last November when she was found running as a stray in Metropolis, Illinois, with another dog and was transferred to TAPS after no one claimed to own her. Given that she was a stray, she had no background information, but we have discovered that she is a sweet, fun, and sassy girl with lots of energy - and so much more! 

I have taken Lois to my home several times, and outside the shelter, I witness a different dog every time - still a sassy dog, but a fun girl! And although Lois is well-adjusted at the shelter, she has the appearance in her kennel of being high-spirited, and extremely excited who will bark excessively to get your attention, but this is the only way she knows how to get your attention. 

For starters, Lois is bursting with anticipation to go for a ride and do something fun and has a cute "snort" when she is overly excited. Lois loves car rides and prefers to ride standing on the center console of my car so she can get a clear view of her surroundings and to see where she is going. Since this is her favorite spot in the car, it is not surprising that when she was transported to TAPS initially, she broke loose from her crate to sit in the front seat. But this is not to say that she does not like to be crated; in fact, she prefers to be in a crate when her kennel is being cleaned. 

Lois is a fun dog with a spunky spirit and personality. At my house, she is extremely curious of her surroundings and relishes at any opportunity to be active. When I first brought her to my house, she showed enormous interest in my swimming pool and, although it was clear she had never swam before, she quickly realized she could swim and smiled the entire time with excitement of her new found activity. From that day after, she made several trips to my house to go swimming and after swimming for nearly an hour, she would then want to go for a hike. Due to her high energy level, she would not be a good fit for adopters that are couch potatoes. And potential adopters should know that Lois can, and will, climb a chain link fence if left unattended. 

With the colder weather, Lois' future visits have been regulated to inside my house where I learned surprisingly new things about her. Since Lois has such a high energy level, I thought she would run through my house, slide across my hardwood hallways knocking over my Christmas decorations, pee on the carpet, and, largely, be too excited to be inside; however, I was pleasantly wrong! After she thoroughly inspected my house, she began to settle in and take the bones that I gave her and piled them by the back door - clearly she wanted to take them outside to perhaps bury or simply save for a later date. Also, to my surprise, she did not pee, or attempt to pee, in my house and when I said "let's go potty outside" she got a look on her face where it was clearly evident she knew what that meant. In hindsight, this should not have surprised me since Lois always has a clean kennel and waits to go potty outside for her morning walk. 

As mentioned earlier, Lois was found running with another dog, so it is presumed she is dog friendly; however, she has had several meet-and-greets with other dogs, and they did not go as well as we had hoped for as we discovered Lois plays very hard with other dogs and does not appear to pick up on other dogs' cues to back down from play. For that reason, it appears that other dogs may not be in Lois' future, however TAPS has not discounted Lois' ability to be with other dogs yet because Lois may be acting like this during the meet-and-greets due to kennel stress and is willing to try another dog introduction in the future. 

During Lois' stay with TAPS, we have also learned that Lois absolutely loves all people that she meets; except small children and we have witnessed her become extremely reactive to small children that have entered the shelter. Given Lois' reaction to small children, we believe she is trying to tell us that she may have been teased by small children in the past. Accordingly, we believe Lois lived in a house with children, although probably not well supervised children, and is potty trained. 

Overall, Lois will make a great companion for anyone who is active, does not have small children (older children are okay), and would most likely not do well in a quiet home with non-energetic people. But if you are a looking for a sassy, fun, well-rounded, active girl - Lois Lane would be perfect!
animal.name: Lois Lane

animal.description:
Hey ya'll! My name is DOVER and I am a little over 2 years old!!! I have been with One Love since I was about 3 months old and all of my brothers and sisters have found their furever homes. Annnddd, I would really, really like to find my person(s) to watch over and love with all my might. So, I have asked my super cool foster mom and dad to help me put into words what would be my perfect fit*(see below)*! Maybe you are wondering why I am still with my foster parents for over a year now. Well, they have told me I have allergies to several things in my environment and they are most likely in everyone's environment, so I eat special food and need allergy shots about every 4-8 weeks depending which part of our lovely Georgia season we are currently in. My skin was a mess when I was waaay younger and I had to go to a place called "the Vet" so often that now I really don't like going there at all. Car rides scare me but I am getting better and can sometimes look out the window when we are going down the road. I am working on meeting new people and trusting them around those I love. I love to play with my foster brother because we have the same "energy" level (it can go from super high to just lounging on the deck watching the birds). I don't understand older dogs who don't want to roughhouse. I know everyone loves kids but they are not for me, can't help it (I don't trust them). I really just need a small family that I can hang out with, watch over and have them watch over me. Let me know if you want to meet!

Dover would do best with a single person or couple without children or a lot of people coming and going, he needs consistency. He needs someone who will watch his skin color and behaviors that will tell when his allergies are getting bad, which can put him in a bad mood because he is miserable (the allergy shots are a savior). Dover is always on alert, until he trusts (a person or situation), so it is hard for him to relax and be the happy go-lucky dog who wants to meet everyone. New situations can overwhelm Dover and he needs to be handled with confidence and attention. He does not like larger crowds of people or dogs. He loves to play - whether it is tug-o-war with a rope or throwing his favorite toy to himself - but also loves to lounge around just knowing you have his back just as much as he has yours. He will always let you know if someone or something is out of the ordinary around the house. Dover is a super handsome and good boy who is just looking for his person to watch over and be best of buds.
animal.name: Dover

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Silly boy FarleyDate into Rescue: Originally 1/6/2017, adopted and returned in 2018
Reason for being in rescue: Farley was originally found as a stray in SC and taken to a local shelter. CPR pulled him from the shelter. Farley was adopted and lived in a home for almost a year. He was returned to CPR in 2018 when his owners were unable to manage his behavior - his epilepsy was just starting and was not controlled
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Farley is an epileptic - controlled. He is takes medication 3 times per day. The medication he is on is called Keppra (generic name Levetiracetam). This can be purchased at Walmart or Chewy.com and runs roughly .35 cents per day). He MUST have his dose every 8 hours so please make sure your schedule allows this.
Weight: about 32 lbs
Height: about 12 in at the shoulder
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $1, I am special

Fence needed? Farley would love a fence to run around in, but it is not a necessity.

What kind of home would be best for me? Farley would do best in a high energy experienced home with no other animals. He is fabulous with people, and wants all the belly rubs in the world! Farley needs a home where he has experienced dog owners, that can manage his behavior and his seizures! He is not to go to a home with a first time dog owner. Farley would do best in a home where there are no kids under the age of 12. He is a lover, but has his moments. He is not aggressive towards people, but he is dog selective and needs to be carefully watched around any dogs. .

What is my personality like? Farley originally came into the rescue from a South Carolina shelter as a stray. He was adopted a few months later but recently returned due to not getting along with other dogs. While he was here with us the first time, Farley got along great with other dogs, but that did not work when he was in a home. We think once he is comfortable in his own space and claims his home he does not like to share his things and will resource guard toys, his crate, and sometimes even people. Other than that he is a joy to be around! Farley is very wiggly and so happy with his caregivers! He really doesn't meet a stranger. He adores toys, especially tennis balls and will play with his toys all day until the cows come home. Farley is also very intelligent, and will do anything for a treat. He knows how to sit, lay down, stay, and possibly even a few more. He loves people, there is not a shy bone in his body. His previous adopters had a wisdom panel DNA test on him. We had him listed as a corgi but it turns out, he is not a Corgi at all! His main breeds are Alaskan Malamute, Chow Chow, Dachshund, Golden/Lab Retriever. A true Heinz 57 pup that is looking for someone to understand his needs. We've left corgi on his description simply because he is long and low looking like a corgi.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly

Other tips and tidbits: Farley has a lot of potential - he just needs an experienced owner to give him a chance!

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description: Rico, male Mixed breed, 2 YO and 24 lbs. Rico arrived as an owner surrender. His owner got him as a gift for their daughter and said she is not taking care of him so they brought him here. He lived with 3 children in the home. ((Poor Baby) Rico has been very snarky here with everyone who tries to interact-but for some reason he loves me. He was very easy for me to leash and in no time he began to play and dance around me. He put his paws on my knees and rubbed his head into my hand to pet him. I had no trouble at all with him and he seemed very grateful for the attention. I asked another staff to visit him and she had no luck becoming his friend. And a few staff were walking towards us in the hallway, and he hard barked and snarked at them. I think he just needs someone to feel safe with and I am hopeful he can transfer his affections he has towards me onto another rescue person! Rico is HW negative. I adore this boy, and he adores me too-but he can be very selective about other human friends. He made a few friends today with a couple other staff who coaxed him with tennis balls. He is definitely better with women and does NOT like people in uniform at all. New pic shows that I can easily handle him and pick him up.

animal.description:
Meet Percy,  Isn’t he a cutie pie? 12 lbs and about 8 years old. He’s very much a smuggler. He would be a great lap dog. He does have “dry eye” and requires drops every day for the rest of his life, but it’s very treatable. Percy needs to be an only dog and he is blind in one eye...but that does not slow him down.

All our pets are spayed or neutered, vaccinated including rabies, given de-wormer, heartworm negative or being treated with the slow kill method approved by our veterinarian, on prevention, on flea/tick prevention, most are house trained. The majority but not all of our pets require a fence. Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered. We adopt within 300 miles of New Orleans/Baton Rouge, La and we do not ship or transport--Adoption fee $200. Email us at creolepoodlerescue@yahoo.com to get an adoption application. Complete an adoption form and email it back to us (we do not have a FAX) if interested in adopting and providing a loving home for this pet.  If you can't email it to us, you can mail it to P.O. Box 2333, Gonzales, La 70707, but this will slow the process down.

When you request an adoption application, we will also send you our guidelines to read - many questions you may have are answered there.  All of our pets are in private foster homes. We require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meeting for any of our pets. Everything we know at this time about this pet is posted.IF YOU SEE THIS PET POSTED ON OUR ADOPTABLE PETS PAGE, THIS PET IS AVAILABLE. WE UPDATE OUR ADOPTABLE PETS SEVERAL TIMES DAILY.  IF THE WORD PENDING IS NEXT TO THE NAME, THE PET HAS AN APPROVED ADOPTER COMING TO MEET AND PROBABLY ADOPT HIM OR HER.  We reserve the right to refuse adoption for any reason.

We are all VOLUNTEERS and have full time jobs, families, pets of our own to care for - we do the best that we can to get back to you in a timely manner.  Please realize that turning in an application today will not mean that you adopt a poodle tomorrow.  We believe in taking the time to go through our thorough process to try to match the dog with the family.

animal.description:
Don't bother buying once of those fancy schmancy mattresses--Dexter will give you the ins and outs of novel sleeping positions!  

We'd like to introduce you to Dexter! No, really, we want you to meet this derpy dude. He's around a year old and weighs about 70 pounds, but definitely a trim 70. He tries to be in tip top shape! 

Dexter is a bit shy when he first meets people, but if you’re nice to him and maybe give him some treats (subtle, right?), he'll love you BIG time! Sometimes he thinks men can be particularly scary to meet, but he's really drawn to them once he realizes they are kind. And that they have treats. Treats help a ton. 

Dexter really is the sweetest, silliest boy. In fact, despite his size, Dexter strongly believes that your lap is his lap and will happily join you for a big slobbery kiss.  

Do you have another canine family member? Dexter has done great with small dogs and we think he can live with bigger dogs, too, but will need a slow and appropriate introduction to any doggy siblings. 
 
Because Dexter can be a bit shy, a low-traffic, adult-only home (or a low-traffic home with older kids) would be best for him. He'd also like a home without cats. He really just doesn't understand those creatures. 

Dexter is an athletic sort of pooch and needs a 6-foot privacy fence because he can be a little bit of an escape artist. He loves to play fetch with a ball, so keeping Dexter and his human(s) entertained is easy peasy. He's super treat motivated, too. (In case you haven't gotten the hint, the way to Dexter's heart is definitely through his stomach. And his stomach likes treats.) 

How about we get together to see if you’re Dexter's forever person/family? 

Call/text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387. He's in the Kansas City metro, but transport is available to the right home. Let's do this!


INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET? Fill out an Adoption Application now! Appointments can also be made to meet a pet by calling us at 913-671-PETS (913-671-7387).  

ADOPTION INFORMATION:
Prior to adoption, our animals are: 
**Tested for diseases 
**Vaccinated 
**Spayed/neutered 
**Microchipped 

NO COST adoptions with an encouraged donation are accepted. 

The Pet Connection also offers adopters a FREE veterinary examination and a medical care support plan for 60 days after adoption, as well as lifetime behavioral training, safe sanctuary for pets returned in emergency situations, extensive assistance with lost and found pets, and other expert pet services in a variety of areas, including pet selection, behavioral issues, general training, nutrition, and transition to adoptive homes.

Please visit our website at www.thepetconnection.org for more information about The Pet Connection and for a full listing of our available pets, 

Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 if you can foster, adopt, or sponsor a special needs dog or cat! 

The Pet Connection is a membership organization operating a no-kill adoption center located in Shawnee, Kansas.

~ THIS IS A COURTESY POST ~ PLZ DO NOT CONTACT MASSPAWS ~
To adopt me, please email my friend Joy at Broken Tails Rescue but be sure to tell her that ARK sent you! joychambers@gmail.com Thank you! #ARKforPearl

Meet Pearl, a 5-6-year old, 50-pound bitty pittie mix living in Framingham, MA! This cutie-patootie has a huge heart, though like some people, she is struggling with anxiety. However, she is growing more confident every day, and is ready to take on life with a fur-ever family.

When you first meet Pearl, she may put on a tough face, barking and growling, but thanks to the training her fosters have provided, she is getting more comfortable and confident. She tries so hard to show her hidden well-behaved, easygoing personality. She will need lots of work to trust strangers, but when she’s with “her” people, she showers them with kisses and cuddles.

Pearl is a smarty-pants who knows “sit,” “paw,” “high-five,” and “down.” Additionally, she is potty trained and muzzle trained. Apart from stranger danger, two areas that still need polishing are jumping on her family and barking due to separation anxiety. However, at her core, Pearl is a faster learner who is motivated by attention and treats. 

Pearl’s typical exercise routine consists of going on short walks, but she also enjoys going on hikes and playing with toys. Afterwards, she likes to relax by sunbathing or lounging on her bed. Though Pearl enjoys a bit of activity, she is non-destructive and fairly low energy, making her well-adapted for less active homes. 

Pearl will flourish with a dog-savvy, experienced owner(s) who can continue to train and socialize her. Pearl very much dislikes strangers and the vet, and though she’s come a long way, it has taken training and occasional medication. Pearl is afraid of crates! They cause  her to panic, and she has injured herself trying to escape them. Should visitors come, Pearl would prefer a hiding spot where she can fly under the radar. 

Pearl’s wish list goes something like this:
•	Quiet adult home without kids, teens, and cats
•	Low-energy dog companion (no hyper pups or dog parks please!)
•	Calm and peaceful home with a comfy spot of her own
•	Lots of snuggles and sweet talk 

If you want a lovable dog with a face you can’t resist and also have a calm and structured home, please email ARK friend Joy at Broken Tails Rescue but be sure to tell her that ARK sent you! joychambers@gmail.com  #ARKforPearl

animal.description:
If interested in adopting Simon please go to our website www.jcldr.com and fill out an adopt application online. We will then contact you. No one is obligated to adopt by filling out the adopt app but it gets us acquainted with you and your life style and expectations to see if he might be a match. 

Simon is an excessive White neutered Catahoula Male, about two years old. Vision and hearing impaired. He does have eccentric pupils. We would say his vision is not crisp, probably his peripheral vision is not very good, has to see right in front of him. Special needs. He can hear dogs bark, he responds to deep tones not high pitched tones. (Admin Note; This is not uncommon with excessive white dogs) Weighs about 63 pounds. He loves the water definitely. He is leash puller, as most Catahoulas are when focused. He has to know the vet and get comfortable with them and then he is easier to handle at the vets.  He settles down. He cannot be manhandled. He is up to date on vaccs, HW tested and HW negative as of January. He rides well in the car like a gentleman. He is an average vocal dog. (Admin note: dogs with hearing deficit usually like the vibration of their own voice but he is not an excessive constant barker) Nail trims and baths are fine and he will let the foster do it herself, he is very good for grooming. He is very easy to handle once he is comfortable in the environment. He adores kids, even interacts with the 3 year old and can’t get enough. We still would want supervision and also respectful children in his world. He loves the foster’s cat but they don’t like him back. He plays Catahoula rough with them and they don’t like him. He is fine with foster’s dogs, but in the outside world and he is unfamiliar in the surroundings that he is dog reactive. Foster has terriers and lab mixes, both male and female in his own environment after SLOW and proper introductions. He is wanting to play with small dogs but is definitely too rough and they don’t like him either the same as the cats. We recommend a female dog that isn’t horribly dominant and bossy, which likes to play rough would be a good fit for him. He is not over protective in the home and actually very friendly to strangers coming and going in the home. He is uneasy about people in public.  He feels safer in the home and he would just as soon stay there. It has to do with contrast and bright lights and his vision. He has been good on hiking trails where there is little to no human and dog traffic. This dog should be ON LEASH AT ALL TIME due to his hearing and vision deficit for his safety and others. He is fed twice a day.  He is crate trained. He may fuss a bit at times, but he responds to the “Harrison Ford point” and settles right down.  It must be an airline approved crate with room in it for him to move around since he is large, His crate now is 48 inches. No open wire crates, he escapes and that is not uncommon for many and most dogs. They can and will. Long distance transport can be discussed.  

HISTORY: The end of 2018 someone found him as a stray a couple of counties over in hunting territory. They could not keep him and the foster met him late at night and to keep him from going to a shelter, she took him. She took care of all his vetting and it was clear that he had separation anxiety. Work was done through meds and training, he did improve and he was kept on the meds for his adoption when that family took him off, probably cold turkey, no weaning. He is on Prozac now and he is doing fine as well. It has to be monitored for side effects which can often be behavior issues though none show up today. He was adopted out in April 2019 to a family that had six other dogs so he was to have exercise and play all the time. Active family. He ended up getting kicked out of day care, because he played rough in overstimulation and that often is misread by dogs and humans. They said they were returning him due to reactions in camp grounds to strangers but foster found out that the family was tense and there was a family break up and they split dogs up. 

GOOD: He is sweet and friendly in the home, generally in the house, housebroken but when he came back from the adopters home he had problem with urinating and it was mostly due to learned day care behavior. That stopped right away with a little work. Easily is re-directed for the most part. He loves toys and he tries to play fetch but has a hard time finding it if he doesn’t see where it lands. He loves the flirt and it doesn’t affect his prey drive as it does some dogs.  Not a digger, but he might follow suit with another dog instigating. He is not a fence crawler or jumper now, but he was at first he was. It was a wood fence 6 foot. He just tried to climb up and out, not jump actually. Easy dog overall and he loves to cuddle, but can be an awkward bed partner with his legs and feet. Nothing bad, just a big goof. He has no control over his limbs. He still thinks he is a puppy. 

BAD: Might mark in a new home until he gets used to it but that is not uncommon in change with any male dog. His overstimulation with dogs and strangers in public can really be strong so he must be removed into a quieter setting but it depends on how much invade his space. He has gotten a lot better and may never be 100%. He does counter surf if food is left in the open, like many Catahoula’s. To him it is a high end game if it is on the counter. He steals anything if he gets bored. One day he stole a bar of soap.  He steals kid’s toys and he will run around and play with them but he does chew them but does definitely try to ingest it internally. So things must be watched and picked up or he could be at risk for a bowel blockage. He cannot have bedding in his crate as it is risky. Foster hasn’t tried except once. Leash pulling.  

UGLY: Worst thing is the out and about reactivity, he needs more work but has gotten so much better with proper training and management. He will do a sit and trust leash handler. He is obnoxious towards other dogs in a Catahoula way and so he has to be separated when he pushes too long and too hard and given a time out.

animal.description:
Hi Everyone! I'm U'ilani.  I know what you are thinking...that might be a tough name to remember. But it is unique and that is a good thing! It means Hawaiian heavenly beauty, and if you decide to meet me you will undoubtedly find that I am as beautiful on the inside as I am on the outside.

Since you are here, looking at my bio, I guess it is safe to assume you are considering adding a dog to your family.  So let me tell you a little something about myself to see if we might be a match for each other.

A proper female usually wouldn't tell a stranger her weight, but I'll tell you since you won't tell anyone else.  You see I'm pretty tiny at just 45 pounds which makes me a great size (not to big, not to small).   And to be honest, it makes me a great size to curl up on your lap!

I am so lucky that I landed an awesome foster home and my foster mom said I am the most amazing girl ever!  I am housebroken, although I'll admit that it took a few days for me to get used to the routine, but now no accidents at all!  I'm sure that is in part because I get a treat every time I go potty outside.  I am told that my eyes get wide and I snort just a little when I get treats, but I'm not sure I believe it.  I am a proper lady after all.  

And low maintenance?  You betcha!   At about 7 years old I am relatively low energy which would make me a fit for almost any lifestyle.  While I love to go for walks I would be just as happy playing in a fenced yard to get my exercise.

And car rides?  Well I just LOVE them!  My foster mom actually hooks up my seat belt and we are on our way.  And I am equally happy curling up on the back seat as I am hanging my head out the window.  Either way it is a win win for me!

I must be pretty special because when my family goes out I don't need to be crated.  I just hang out and relax, keeping an eye on the place while they are gone.  And at night I get to sleep in the oversized chair in the living room.  I'm only allowed on the loveseat if someone is in the den and I totally respect the house rules.  But to be honest I can't wait for someone to sit with me because my very favorite thing in the whole wide world is to cuddle!  I absolutely LOVE to be right next to my people.  I would certainly do a good job keeping your feet warm while we hang out this winter watching Netflix!

I don't have any interest playing with toys so you won't spend a lot of money on things to entertain me.  To be honest, I would just be content with your love and attention.  I would do best in a home as the only dog.  I'm not rude or obnoxious while walking and passing other dogs, I just prefer to be the only canine in the house.  A home with out kitties would also be best as I can get a little to focused on little fuzzy creatures.  

Well that pretty much sums me up.  Absolute sweet heart cuddle bug who would love to share the couch with you!  So if you think that you and I might be a match, don't hesitate to fill out an application to adopt!  You will be happy you did.

animal.description:
I'm as pretty as a flower and as sweet as a bowl of ice cream! I am a 65 lb , 4-5 yr old chubby hound mix and my coat has the most beautiful markings. I am the best family gal in the world. I love kids, love to cuddle on the couch or chair with my family. I had my own person all my life until they passed away, and then ended up in a shelter. I was not happy there at all... Thats when the nice people at BBRH rescued me! One of my favorite things to do is snuggle up close to you and roll around to get belly rubs. It has been determined that I live my best life if I am an only dog in the house. I just dont love others doggies as much as I love my humans. Cat mesmorize me so I need to stay away from those too, I just cant settle with a kitty around! I am a good listener and will follow you from room to room. I love to feel part of a family and want to protect you.

On a leash I can pull and bark at other doggos so need continued work on this, as I love going on walks. I have never had an accident in the house and will go to the door when I need to go out. If you are not paying attention and I really need to go, I will paw at you. I love car rides, cool floors, watching TV, and couches.

When my foster parents leave, I get a little anxious in a kennel and do not love to be in one, so they leave me out in the house and I am just fine. After barking for a bit I calm down quickly. When you get home I talk to you and tell you how much I missed you, and show you my toothy grin, dance around and tell you how much I missed you! Cutest thing ever. All around I am the greatest dog ever is what my foster family says.

I am 4-5 years old, up to date on all my shots, microchipped and free of heartworms. Are you my new forever family? I would love a home, with a fenced in yard and I guarantee many kisses in exchange for belly rubs! I am being fostered in Sioux Falls SD. Applications can be filled out at bassetandbeagle.org , Adoption fee $250 .

animal.description:
Bobby was rescued from the Downey Shelter where he was so scared and fearful, the shelter said he was not available for public adoption due to being unsocial, but poor Bobby was just very misunderstood. Bobby needs an adopter who is an experienced dog owner and must live in the Temecula/Wildomar/Murrieta/Lake Elsinore area because Bobby's adoption comes with 4-6 weeks of specialized training for the adopter. Bobby was never handled or cared for by a person before, so he needs strict guidance on who is alpha and he needs rules and boundaries or he gets confused. I tried for a year to work with Bobby, but it wasn't until he went to a specialized trainer/handler for 10 days that he truly flourished. He is a completely different dog now and it was because I was doing everything wrong! Bobby weighs about 12 pounds and is approximately 4-5 years old. He is sweet and loves his belly rubs. He loves his toys and walks and is housetrained. He crates perfectly. He likes both men and women equally. Bobby needs to be an only dog or with another dog who is NOT an alpha (he likes to play with other dogs, but is very fearful of larger alpha dogs)and we do not want Bobby to be adopted into a family with children or who will have younger grandchildren coming around (although he seems to love children, they might grab at him or hurt him and he will nip in fright). Bobby is very loyal, loves the outside and is a beautiful little dog that deserves a second chance at a happy life. For more information, please call (951) 678-7497 or fill out an application at GreenDogFoundation.org and we will get back to you as soon as we can. Thank you for looking to adopt!

animal.description:
Birdman was seized in an animal cruelty investigation. He was one of the worst cases of animal abuse and cruelty that we've ever seen. He had many open wounds all over his body, had sustained some kind of burns, had scars and we even found a bullet in his head! He was absolutely terrified of everything. It has been 6 months since we rescued him, and his physical wounds have healed but not all of his hair will grow back over them. He wags his tail and is definitely more comfortable around everyone that he knows. He absolutely loves being with other dogs and will start playing with them right away.(Check out his video!)  His spirits are good and we are amazed at his incredible recovery. He is such a sweet boy but still a little nervous around people he doesn't know well, especially men. He is terrified of them and once jumped our fence when he saw one! Therefore, he will also need a very tall and secure fence. Birdman would do best in a quiet home and  he really needs to have a routine.  

His date of birth is 2/24/2017 and he weighs about 71 pounds. 

You can submit an adoption application for this handsome boy at http://www.fayettefcar.com/applicationform, where you can also review FCAR’s adoption requirements.

All FCAR adoptable dogs have been spayed or neutered, are current on all vaccines, on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, microchipped, and come with a 30-day pet health guarantee. The adoption fee is $95 with an approved application. A fenced yard is required for Birdman.

animal.description:
Eclipse showed up at a Good Samaritan's home, scarred up all over, face, body, everywhere.  Emaciated to the point all her ribs were  easily visible.   Scared, alone, and hungry, she made it to a home where people fed her, gave her a bed, and reached out to us for help. 
Obviously we feel strongly she was a bait dog at one time.. Surprisingly with slow intros to large dogs she is okay.   She does go into protection mode quickly though.
She is very sweet to humans.  Loves attention and so deserves a special place to call home
The on line application for her adoption is below. Please note, we do the following
1. on line application
2. vet and reference check
3. phone call
4. home visit
5 meet and greet
6. adoption

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
FOSTER UPDATE JANUARY 3, 2021

She's a wonderful dog, with a ton of personality, and she will make a great companion.
She runs in the fenced yard when she's chasing a squirrel up the tree, and she trots quickly in the house if she hears someone call her, but she doesn't run or get rowdy in the house.
She knows the furniture she's allowed to get on. She will put her head under my hand until I pet her. Her favorite type of toy is a stuffed squeaky toy. She doesn't tear them up; she just carries them around, and plays with them by herself. She will also hold a ball in her mouth, but she doesn't like fetch. She's never torn anything up, and she hasn't taken anything that didn't belong to her since those early days. She loves to eat and is always hungry. She loves broccoli stems! She's food motivated and smart, so it is easy to teach her new tricks. She seems so sweet and gentle that you don't imagine she will steal food, but she's not so innocent that you can turn your back on her.
She is a pretty good leash walker. She doesn't pull much; in fact, she tends to want to go slower than we do. When she sees a squirrel, she stalks it, until we get close. I have to tell her, "no" and break her concentration or she will jerk at the leash trying to chase it.
She is well trained and will sit to be petted or for a treat. When she's thinking of jumping on you, if you put your hand out she will stop and sit in front of you. She comes when you call her. As far as other dogs go, she likes people better and would be best as the only dog.
You've seen videos of dogs who are wracked with guilt after they do something wrong, and Mama Tig is like that, hanging her head when she has done something wrong.
She knows when we are going out and makes herself scarce so we won't put her in her crate (although she lounges in it all day long). Finally we tell her, "Yes, Mama Tig, you have to go in the crate." And she looks up at us, sighs heavily and walks toward it. She'll look back at us with her most sweet expression, like, really? I have to?
Mama Tig will make a great companion, staying by your side as long as you want her there, and then just a smidge longer. She's friendly, happy, loving and loyal. You will not regret letting her into your life.============================================

Mama Tig has been in our foster home for a couple of months now, and she is very happy to get attention from anyone in the house. She is the official greeter of the teenagers when they wander out of their rooms. 'I love this dog!' my son says, 'She's always happy to see me.'
Mama Tig has two main expressions; Please, please pet me! and Oh, wow, they're petting me! This is heaven!!
She takes correction well, and has learned to leave the trash alone and stay away from the possum holes under the fence.
My daughter is taking online classes, and Mama Tig is there in the WebEx screen, making sure she gets plenty of attention, but unobtrusive enough that she doesn't get shooed out of the room.
Mama Tig is having more bursts of energy than she did when we first started fostering her. She will sprint across the backyard in sheer joy, then come running back to me, smiling and excited. She's been well trained to sit and wait for attention, and even when she's excited, a quick hand motion will remind her of her manners. She is still calm and mellow most of the time, and doesn't run or get rowdy inside the house.
We think Mama would be best as only dog since we have not been able to find a suitable match Foster Home Update: We really love Mama Tig. She became attached to us so quickly, and she just seems to be ready to love and be loved. She walks up to you and sits politely at your feet and turns her face up to you. You cannot resist petting her. She's just a lovely cuddlebug. She is an escape artist! Her new parents are going to have to be very careful at the front door when entering or exiting!

Mama Tig is fully housetrained. I take her out regularly, but if she ever needs to go out, she will let us know by whining at the door. She loves toys, especially squeaky rubber toys. She's extremely gentle with everything she does, and she will kiss your face if you let her. She also knows what she's doing wrong when you tell her no, such as going into a room she's not allowed, and she comes when called.
We've had Mama Tig in our house for a bit now, and we've been able to see more of her personality. She's very loving, mellow, gentle. She melts like a puddle, slipping down to the floor, when you pet her in an especially good spot, and she teenage daughter's hugs. In the house, she's calm, docile, and accommodating, right there if you want to snuggle and watch tv, but just as content alone in her dog bed. Occasionally, she gets in a playful mood and carries around one of her squeaky toys, tossing it and squeaking it with her mouth. She'll chase it a couple of times if you squeak it and throw it, but she's not completely sold on the idea of giving her toy back and would just as soon keep it and squeak it herself!
She's a good leash walker, and loves heading out the front door, but she's not the dog for someone who wants to take long walks. She's ready to head home after a block or two. She pulls a little bit when we pass another dog or a squirrel, and she chases squirrels up the trees in the backyard.
Mama Tig is loving and gentle, calm and easy, with just enough personality to make you laugh or marvel at her, but not so much that you've got messes to clean! Her main personality is mellow, but she does get excited-about toys, walks, and charmingly, she gets excited at every reunion with someone, even if it's just that she's been in the other room for a couple of hours. Seeing her smiling face and wagging tail greet you when you get back after hours or a 30 second walk to the mailbox is delightful. She will add so much love to her forever family. Come and meet her, maybe it will be you
----------------
Mama Tig is currently heartworm positive, but please do not let that shy you away from this wonderful dog! Pet Rescue By Judy practices the slow kill method for treating heartworm, and we have had great success with it. The slow kill method means we give the infected dog a medication for 30 days (if you adopt within his first 30 days we will provide you with the medication) and then after that all she needs is her monthly heartworm preventative medication.

animal.description:
Anthony is a one-of-a-kind - He's definitely unique-looking! His personality is just as bold as his looks, and this will require someone patient and experienced. 

Anthony arrived at the HSEP from the city shelter at Animal Services with an unknown history since his owner failed to reclaim him. As Anthony spent more time here at the shelter, our staff noticed he was not acclimating well to all the noise and stress that comes with living in a shelter, and he also had what some might call ""stranger danger"" - He was hesitant to trust new people in his life, and so he displayed undesirable behavior in an effort to feel safe, which is a complete 180 from the lovable goofball that all the Animal Care Associates know and love. We found that Anthony was treat motivated, but he won't accept treats from people that are either lacking confidence or impatient and just want to start playing with him without yet earning his trust. So how do you get to be one of the people he loves? Ask an Animal Care Associate to meet with him, and they'll utilize one of our quieter rooms so Anthony can just focus on learning about you. Don't forget the treats!

Anthony Davis isn't a fan of cats or smaller pets, but he seems to be able to coexist with dogs his size as long as they have doggie manners and aren't overwhelming. To ensure compatibility, a Meet + Greet with any dogs you have at home is required prior to adoption. 

Anthony knows the command ""sit"", and is also housetrained! He's working on learning to love his crate, and positive reinforcement will go a long way. This means using all the things he loves (such as meals and toys) to get him to willingly go inside his crate because after all, that should be his safe lounging place. 

If you've got a patient heart with plenty of love to give to a dog that needs a second chance, ask an Animal Care Associate to meet Anthony!
Happiness Happens at the Humane Society of El Paso!

animal.description:
DAISY was found on one of the reservations we work with along with her sister (who hears) and her brother (who is also blue-eyed and deaf). She is very sweet, lots of waggy tails, happy, playful and lots of kisses :-). 

She identifies you by smelling you and once she recognizes you, lavishes you with kisses :-) She has a comical nature as you can see from the pictures :-)   You will need to have another friendly playful young dog - puppies need to play and a deaf dog needs a best friend to be her ears. If you don't have another dog, Daisy has two best friends in foster that she plays with daily-- Foley and Ollie.

 A great site with tips on having a deaf dog family member is DeafDogsRock.com and there's quite a bit of DDSL on there as well. There are also a few books on Amazon about deaf dogs as family members. 

 Daisy has play dates with other dogs daily and has a great time! She's also been fostered with cats.  Daisy is deaf and has trouble seeing when she comes inside from a strong sun (her eyes are very pale blue :-) 

Her adoption fee includes her spay, vaccines, deworming, tick/flea prevention, and microchip. Her birthday is January 30, 2020.   

Important:
Do you live in our adopting area? Do you have another young playful friendly male dog? If yes to both questions, then please proceed with the application process below! :-)

We're sorry, but if you email us or fill out an application that does not fit the parameters of our procedures we will not be replying to you. Thank you for your understanding!

We have specific adoption and Covid rules listed below.

Revised adoption policy
Due to Covid -19 pandemic and social distancing requirements, we've revised our adoption policy. First, please email (desertpawsnm@gmail.com) to inquire before you fill out the online application. (Please do not call or text). We are unable to do multi-dog/cat meetgreets or adoption events at this time or bring multiple animals to your house to choose from, so please only inquire if you're serious about adopting this particular animal(s). If you're just shopping around with several shelters and rescues, please let us know this. If your application is approved (which "could" take up to one week) then we will contact you to set up a Zoom chat or ph call to answer questions/clarify anything and set up a day/time to bring the pet to you. Since we can't come into the home/yard due to Covid-19, we ask that you to send us pics /video of your home/yard/living area/current pets. We will discuss with you about meeting your other pets. At the meeting/adoption at your house (outside) please wear a mask (as will we) and have hand sanitizer.

We adopt locally to Central Abq, Santa Fe, Los Alamos and Rio Rancho. No out of area adoptions inquiries please. No young children for our adoptions please. Puppies MUST adopt to families that have another young friendly playful dog of similar size when grown. These animals are fostered and our families like to know their fosters are happy, healthy, and cared for during their lifetime. We appreciate staying in touch periodically (social media, pics, holiday card, videos  etc :-)

Thank you!

animal.description:
We adopt ONLY in the Greater St. Louis Area.

Meg arrived in to rescue with a multitude of skin issues, allergies, early onset of arthritis and anxiety. Through many vet appointments, we have been able to determine underlying medical conditions that are being managed with daily medications and a special diet. Because of this, we do consider Meg to be Special Needs and will require medication and a special diet the rest of her life. We would be happy to discuss Megan's medical needs.

Despite her medical conditions, Meg is a sweet, bright Corgi girl. True to the Corgi breed, she is intelligent, easy to train, and eager to please. She is active in her backyard, chasing the birds, squirrels and running the fence with the neighbor dog. She has no issues with steps or getting up on the sofa to snuggle. She enjoys daily short walks, playing fetch and tug of war with her toys. She is quiet in the house, unless she is ready for a romp in the yard outside. She can be anxious in new situations, and prefers some personal space with the other older dogs in the house. She would probably be best as an only dog or paired with one laid back dog that would give her some space. She is also fine with the cats in the home. She is crate-trained and house-trained, up-to-date on vaccines and heartworm preventative. Megan is 8 years old.

Please read our website information at www.petssecondchance.org before calling about Meg. We require a fenced yard and no small children. Contact claireelizabeth@petssecondchance.org for more information or to inquire about adoption.

animal.description:
We are currently open by appointment only. Please call us at 623-872-7941 and schedule a time to come and view our animals.

Our adoption process
Step 1: Please fill out an application.
Step 2: Interview with adoption counselor.
Step 3: If you're the right match, you may be able to meet the animal today, or set up an appointment to meet the animal when we have more time available to ensure it's the right match.
Step 4: Depending on your home and readiness, you may be able to take an animal home today.
*Please note that due to a high volume of interest in some of our animals, we may take multiple applications to ensure everyone gets a chance to apply and be interviewed. We don't do our adoptions on first come first serve basis, we instead focus on matchmaking to ensure the perfect match for both the animal and adopter.

DOB: 6/6/2014
Breed: Staffordshire Terrier Mix
Spayed Female
Adoption Fee: $200

A little bit about me...

Hello friends! In case we haven't met before, allow me to introduce myself...I'm Helga, and I have been here at the shelter for over two years now. Why am I still here you ask? Most people assume that I mustn't be a nice dog because I bark in my kennel; and even though the other dogs bark in their kennels, they get adopted. If you were in a kennel with people walking past you all day, wouldn't you bark as well? I'm staying positive though because I am looking for someone who understands that I am not a mean dog, but rather a very sweet loving girl who LOVES every single person I meet.

The highlights...

Breed experience preferred
I am addicted to playing frisbee & ball
I love belly rubs and snuggles!
I can go home with mature, older kids
I have a lot of love to give so I'd prefer to be an only dog
I am a restricted breed, so you must own your home.

My ideal home would include...

A family that understands that while I may be an adult, I still need to get used to a new environment and learn when and where I am expected to go potty. I will need to adjust to a whole new routine, and you will need to learn my signs for letting you know I have to go outside to potty.

Someone who will provide me daily walks, a lot of love, and most importantly, treats. I'm a really smart girl and I already know how to sit, lie down, drop it, shake, leave it, stay, as well as other commands. I will need the most help with adapting to a home environment as I've become accustomed to living in a shelter.

Someone who is looking for an amazing dog to accompany them on walks and play fetch with. I enjoy being the center of attention, and I love an audience (and round of applause) when I'm catching frisbees. After a tiring game of fetch I would love to snuggle with you and take a nap!

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Anubis! I am calm, sweet, stocky boy looking to cuddle with my humans and relax in the sun. I am originally from Texas but traveled up north when hurricanes hit in Houston. My favorite hobbies include testing out squeaky toys, playing tug, and watching the bunny rabbits in the backyard. I'm also well mannered in the home and can be trusted left loose when you are at work! I'll also wait until you tell me it's okay for me to join you on the couch for snuggles - that's just how polite I am! Different records have indicated varying ages for me, but I am definitely older than 5 and have the energy of a middle-aged dog.

I do have some fears, big live stock puts me on edge, other dogs make me feel like I need to protect my humans, and little humans make a bit too many fast moves for me to handle in my old age. When I see other dogs out and about, I do react but my foster mom says I am making steady progress with my training and it's a good thing I only need 1-2 short walks a day. I am excellent with kids 5 and up! I am gentle and loving and I adore them.

I am currently on some allergy medication to help get my skin and ears nice and healthy again. Because some allergies require long term management with medication, my meds may need continued on a chronic level, but my foster mom says I don't mind taking them!

I'd love a home where I can be given endless treats and endless love, I will return it ten-fold. I am looking for a foster-to-adopt home, if you are interested please contact Until They're Home or complete the foster/adopt application here

They trained him with 3 different trainers with prongcollars and clearly yanked him . What is against our policy .

He was good before with dogs and suddenly became reactive .

I started to work from zero again on him and he did fine with me . The only problem he still has is that he gets kennel crazy and he shows his anxiety .

Amalto needs a dedicated adopter who has an active lifestyle , who is retired or works from home . It’s clear that he has abandoning issues .

It broke my heart to see our dog returned like this .

Amalto was good before with dogs but starts to bark now on them . He is not good with cats . Amalto is a medium sized dog but looks bigger in picture

He is located in Middle Island NY

We are looking for a person who gains his trust and wants a partner for life .

Amalto loves to be cuddled when he knows you . Is easy on the leash . Knows his basic commends and his house trained .

If you are the person who wants to give Amalto a new chance in life and give him the life he deserves then please apply by filling in the adoption  link to find on our website www.a-teameliterescuedogs.com or email us and we send you one

animal.description: Mac is a young dog, 2 years of age, who is full of life. He loves everyone.  He is a wonderful household dog.  Mac came to Illinois Humane from local animal control, when he partially tore the left hind leg cranial cruciate ligament (CCL) and needed corrective surgery.  The leg is now in good shape.  Mac has a great pitty smile full of that long tongue,   He listens and minds well, and already knows some training tricks that help manage his young dog energy.  He is sensitive, and attentive; he responds well to commands and he responds to his name.  There are two caveats with Mac.  First, important behaviorally, Mac tends toward separation anxiety.  Mac has had to move around too much in his young life, and is not happy to see his humans leave him.  Second, Mac, as it goes with these cases, if they tear one cruciate ligament, there is a chance the other hind leg may have issues down the road.  Just something to keep in mind !

My name is Sherman and I'm a dapper 4/5 yr M Brindle Amstaff/HoundX. I'm 65 lbs of PURE HAPPY HAPPY JOY JOY!! I'm a silly sweet friendly fun loving boy. I'm fine with other dogs but I am a bit pushy so another large dog with similar energy would be great to be with. I would be best with older kids ages 12 yrs+ as I'm a bit strong for young kids. I'm looking for someone who knows, understands and appreciates my breed and wants a partner in outdoor activity.. It would be great to have a fenced in yard for endless fetching sessions! animal.description: Millie is a small, adult female who has a bit of a complicated past.  She was adopted but had behavioral issues over the year she was in the home.  The good news is that she is housebroken, has some training, and gets along with most other dogs (although she will bark at other dogs on the other side of the fence). The bad news is that she does have a bite history.  She isn't reliable with strangers and needs very firm boundaries with everyone in the household.  She is affectionate but she becomes overwhelmed easily, especially when anyone's face is too close.  She will need an adult home with absolutely no interactions with kids.  She also needs a quiet place to be if any visitors come over so she (and them) aren't placed in any uncomfortable situations.  Millie is not an evil dog and she has never been a danger to anyone during her time at the rescue but home life is different and we want to see her succeed.  It isn't just about finding A home for Millie, it is about finding the RIGHT home for her.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.TxDot contacted us about a dog that was residing on their campus for over a month. Traci Bell volunteered to capture her. We named her Dottie.

Dottie was very lucky because the TxDot employees were taking care of her. They were concerned because they saw her walking on the main road.

When Traci caught Dottie, Dottie was not happy. Traci was afraid she would escape the trap. When she got here, she really didn't want anything to do with us.

Within an hour of being on the ranch, Dottie was learning all about walking on a leash and being loved on. She has taken to Kim Young Pagenkopf. Follows her everywhere. Loves other dogs and is going to be ready for a family within a couple of weeks. She is a great dog. However she is heartworm positive.

If you are interested in adopting Dottie, you can fill out an application at www.adoggie4you.org.
Dottie's adoption fee is $200 and she will be coming with her heartworm meds for a slow treat.

&


We are not a shelter, we are a rescue and all of our rescued pets live with a Tennessee foster family until their forever home is found. They are all checked by a veterinarian, current on their vaccinations, spayed/neutered are micro-chipped. Our fosters know the animals best and will give you an honest assessment of their traits and training. 


If you are interested in adopting a pet from Saving The Animals Together, please submit an application by clicking on the Adopt tab at www.savingtheanimalstogether.org or email us at statadoptions@savingtheanimalstogether.org

I don't mind cats but I can be a little too playful so perhaps a home without cats would be best because I wouldn't want to hurt them playing. So please feed me separately if there are other animals in the home. I enjoy toys but only for solitary playtime only. I can not be crated as I find them too confining and stressful. 

I do NOT like to be touched on my back and hind end, so combining that with my high energy, lack of sharing skills, I must go to an adult only home without children. A confident owner with husky experience is best suited for a successful outcome. 

I am looking for that special someone XOXO.

animal.description: Documentary film enthusiast, shares global warming articles on Facebook. Medical marijuana patient, drives a Prius #FeelTheBern -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Intake Date: 1 June 2020 ——- Age: 3 yrs ----- Breed: lab x great Pyrenees ----- Size: 100 lbs ----- Status: owner surrender ----- Compatible with: dogs, older children. No cats. ----- Suitable for: home with a securely fenced yard. ——- Medical/Behavioral Needs: Needs a firm owner, boundaries, consistency. ----- Additional Notes: This polar bear of a dog came to rescue after being bounced a few times. A foster home took him in as an owner surrender for another rescue, but the rescue closed leaving the foster with a dog that is not a great fit for their household long term. Booser is a fun loving, giant goof ball of a dog, but he does have a few quirks that come along with owning a guarding breed. While generally friendly and excited to meet new people, Booser can be reactive at barriers, such as a fence line or through his kennel, with people he doesn't know. As he has settled in over time, these behaviors have diminished, but it is possible they could resurface in a new home. Once Booser knows you, you are his best friend and he'd love to hang with you. He enjoys going for walks and basking in the yard, watching the world go by. Booser requires a slower introduction with new dogs, as he can get a little overwhelmed at too many coming at him too fast, but once he knows a dog, he is a submissive teddy bear. He also doesn't know just how big of a floof he is, so action around young children. Booser walks okay on a leash. Once in a while, he likes to practice bounding around like the mini pony he is, but he quickly composes himself. Booser is generally quiet in the house and not a barker (as a note, he is currently fostered in a rural area so there also isn't a whole lot going on). Booser deserves a home that will love him for the big, fluffy, shed-everywhere, class clown of a dog that he is. -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- If interested in meeting and potentially adopting please read the adoption requirements and complete the adoption application located at forbellessake.org. Once processed and approved a meet and greet can be scheduled and if a match an adoption is finalized at that time. FBS standard adoption fee is $175 and all dogs are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and treated for any known medical needs. Breeds are not guaranteed but often a best guess. Housetraining is not guaranteed but crate training is worked on with all residents. A securely fenced yard is mandatory. --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

animal.description:
Eve is about 2 years old. She came to us from a horrific situation. She was found in the basement of an abandoned bar along with Adam. We have no idea how they got there but do feel they were dumped. They would not have been able to get in that situation by themselves. We believe they are related.....either father/daughter or siblings. They were very skinny when found.

Eve is doing great now. Both she and Adam have vision impairment but hers is definitely less severe.  She adapts quickly to a new situation and relies heavily on her sense of hearing and smell to familiarize herself to new surroundings. She loves to play with other dogs but does best with bigger dogs. She does not do well with cats. Eve must have a fenced yard and does best with a controlled, predictable environment. Due to her vision issues, she can be a bit reactive to new people so will need a slow, calm introduction. She is not aggressive but does react defensively by barking and backing off a bit when she senses a new voice or smell in her surroundings.  

Eve is spayed, HW negative and up to date on shots. For more information, please contact tamjov9@aol.com.

I’m quite the little guard dog and am very protective of the people I love. Even though I’m about 55-60 pounds, I think I’m a lapdog and enjoy cuddles! 

I do not like other dogs and need to be kept away from them, please. I can sit, lie down,stay and my foster family has taught me how to heel. I’m very smart and a quick learner. I love going on daily walks, riding in the car, playing fetch, swimming in shallow water, going out in nature, and chewing durable dog toys. 

I’ll need an active family, as I get bored sitting around the house. I also need a fenced in backyard to run around in and would like to live in a house not an apartment. I’m an adorable, sweetheart who would love to have a somewhat active, loving family without other animals. Please adopt me!

07/31/2020 Rain went in for a dental today and is now toothless. No crunchy kibble for this sweetheart. She is a sweet little girl who wants nothing but your love and attention. She is working on her house manners but doing much better. She still has accidents but we blame that on the human who doesn't keep her on a schedule. She walks well on a leash but loves being able to run free in a fenced area. Her foster family feels a home with a fenced yard would be best for her. Rain gets a little preoccupied and doesn't come when called so needs a little training with recall. Vincent arrived at Horse Creek Wildlife on May 13, 2020.  He is a handsome boy with a heart of gold.  We believe he is possibly a Catahoula Leopard Dog/Boxer mix.

He is extremely sweet and loving.  He never meets a stranger and believes everyone should love him instantly!  He enjoys playing in the exercise areas with other dogs, and he loves spending time with people and going for long walks along our walking trail.

Vincent will make an awesome addition to the family that promises to love and care for him always!  Could that family be yours?

All of our dogs are spayed or neutered and are current on all vaccinations. They are on monthly heartworm and flea/tick prevention. All of their medical needs are taken care of before they are available for adoption. Our adoption fee is only $100.00. Please complete an application, if you have found a dog you are interested in adopting. You can find our application at www.horsecreekwildlife.org/applic.html. Once completed, you can forward it to adoptions@horsecreekwildlife.org or fax it to 731-926-3000. Kim Austin, our adoption facilitator, will be in contact with you as soon as she has an opportunity to review your application. Understand that she has other duties and she will not ignore any interest shown in adopting one of our dogs. An application will need to be approved before a scheduled time to visit our dogs will be set up.  It may take up to 48 hours before she returns your call or responds to your email, due to work schedules, holidays and adoption events. We do the very best we can for the dogs we have rescued and do not take the adoption process lightly. Please be patient and understand that we will place our rescued dogs in the very best homes possible and reserve the right to refuse applications.

Breed: Pitbull Mix
Gender: male, neutered
Estimated DOB: 5/1/11
Vaccinations: up to date
Heartworm Status: negative
Microchipped: yes
Notes:  Can have food and toy aggression and is very selective with dogs and would be best in a home without other dogs.

Hank is not a CAAWS dog but a courtesy listing.  Email his caretaker at lucasapwieser@gmail.com to inquire about adopting or for more information. He is located in New Orleans.
 
Information from caretaker:
Hank is a super loving boy who would do best in a home with lots of space to run and play. He loves all toys and playing fetch and tug-o-war. He is high energy and loves all the walks/jogs he can get but also loves to snuggle up on the couch to watch TV. He is very obedient about certain things - he will run right into his crate when you tell him. He comes, sits, and stays very well. He is not destructive at all and has never chewed something he wasn't supposed to. He has had some issues with food/toy aggressiveness (especially if he has a new bone treat) and would benefit from obedience training. He gets along with some dogs no problem and will run and play for hours, while others he will be aggressive towards right away. Overall Hank is very affectionate and wants to be close to all people he encounters.

Hank is super loving towards all people, including children, but if he were chewing a bone and a child approached unexpectedly or from behind he may get aggressive. Dogs are hit or miss whether he will get along. He has lived with a cat before and will chase them but won't get aggressive with them as far as I know.

IF YOU SAID YES THEN WE'VE GOT JUST THE PAIR OF LOVE BUGS FOR YOU... LOLLI PUP AND HER TWIN BROTHER MEAT BALL ARE LITTLE WRINKLY ROLLEY POLLEY CHARACTERS THAT ARE SIMPLY ADORABLE. LOLLI BEING THE BIGGER OF THE TWO SHE IS ALL WHITE WITH A BROWNISH/BLUE SPOT OVER HER EYE WHEREAS HER BROTHER IS A MIXTURE OF BLUE & WHITE COLORED FUR THAT LOOKS LIKE A MASSIVE SEA OF WRINKLES THAT NEVER ENDS. Barack

is a handsome, loving fawn male. He shows caution upon meeting new people by heavy barking and requires slow introductions with new people. He has made excellent progress working with his trainer, and he will need to continue with his training work in a new adoptive home.

Barack will need to be in a home where he has access to a yard with a secure privacy fence and locked gate, along with daily walkies to maintain his mobility as he ages. He is taking hip/joint supplements for hip arthritis.

animal.description: Meet Stone. Stone has been at Satchel's for a little over 6 months now. Surrendered to us through Beach Vet by his owners who felt he was just too much for them to handle. It takes a few visits with Stone for him to start to earn your trust but this boy is worth the effort. He's a handsome, strong, energetic, young boy with so much life to live. Stone loves to play fetch with tennis balls, but hasn't quite caught onto the entire game - dropping them for you doesn't currently happen so you need to have several. He loves playing 'catch me if you can in the yard' with you, but he is just learning how to play with people and can get wound up quickly, so it is important to keep some level of calmness until he knows how to calm himself. He likes to go on walks with our volunteers, and walks well on a leash, but is very unsure of everything outside of his immediate environment so won't travel far from the shelter. Stone loves all toys, his favorite being the Kong. He will chew on one all day, even if it's empty. Throws it around his kennel, carries it outside with him and brings it back in. He is starting to show affection as he learns to trust. He will come and sit next to you and will lick your face to say 'thank you for saving me'. Stone is still very scared of most things. This young boy needs encouragement and socialization. If you have the time and patience to give Stone what he needs so he is able to become the best boy he can be and enjoy life to the fullest, please set up an appointment to meet him. Email adoptions@satchelslastresort.org or call 941-924-5070.

A TRUE GEM

SUGA PIE HUNEY PUP ALSO KNOWN AS SUGA FOR SHORT, HAS A CALM, LAID BACK NATURE AND LOVES PEOPLE AS WELL AS OTHER DOGS ALIKE. SHE WOULD MAKE A WONDERFUL COMPANION FOR A ACTIVE RETIREE OR UNEMPLOYED INDIVIDUAL. IN ADDITION SHE WOULD BE GREAT AS AN ADDITION TO ANY FAMILY HOUSE HOLD TOO! HER LEGS TALLER THAN MOST COME FROM HER PARENTS WHOM ARE STILL SMALL IN STATURE AS ADULTS WHICH MEANS SHE TOO WILL BE THE AVERAGE SIZE OF AN ADULT JRT. YOUNG AND PLAYFUL SUGA IS KIND SWEET AND LOVING ALL DAY THROUGH. HER GENUINE PERSONALITY AND SAD DROOPY EYES WILL MELT YOUR HEART. SHE LIKE HER GRANDMOTHER HAS INHERITED A SMALL GENETIC GREEN KNOWN CONDITION CALLED "CHERRY EYE" WHICH IS THE REASON FOR HER EYES LOOKING RED AND SWOLLEN. THANKFULLY THIS CONDITION IS NOT PAINFUL AND CAN BE TREATED BUT AS GENETICS PLAYS A ROLE IN THIS SUGA LIKE MOST OTHERS MAY HAVE HER CONDITION FIXED ONLY FOR IT TO RETURN AGAIN IN THE NEAR FUTURE. THIS DOES NOT CAUSE HER ANY ISSUES EXCEPT THAT SHE NEEDS HR EYES CLEANED IN THE MORNINGS OR AFTER WAKING UP TO AVOID ANY INFECTIONS OR TEMPORARY EYE CLOSURES. AS SHE IS 3 MONTHS OLD THE CHERRY EYE HAS OCCURRED VERY EARLY ON IN HER LIFE BUT LIKE OTHERS IN HER FAMILY SHE HAS CONTINUED TO LIVE HER LIFE EACH DAY WITHOUT SKIPPING A BEAT. SUGA WILL NEED TO CONTINUED HOUSE BREAKING AND OBEDIENCE TRAINING FOR HER TO GROW INTO HER BEST ADULT SELF THUS A ROUTINE SCHEDULE WE RECOMMEND FOR SHE AND HER SIBLINGS UPON BEING ADOPTED. SO, IF YOUR LOOKING FOR A LIFELONG FRIEND IN AN EXISTING SMALL DOG THEN YOUR IN LUCK AS OUR SWEETHEART IS A TRUE GEM AND CATCH OF THE DAY!

animal.description:
Sweetie was picked up as a stray, along with her Mother and sister. All three were nursed back to health and are ready for their forever homes. Sweetie is painfully shy. Just no other way to describe her. It may be that she was not handled at all as a puppy, and did not become accustomed to being handled. She greets you by crouching in a low stance and tail tucked.  With time, she warms up and soon begins to wag her tail in greeting. With much love and patience she will grow into a great companion pet.  Age 2 year approximately. 
 Weight 37 pounds. 

Because of her nervous nature, we are recommending a home without young, unpredictable children. She walks fairly nice on a leash. Barks at new sights and sounds, but then stops. Enjoys romping in the yard, and you can see her white tipped tail at attention checking fence line. A true hound!  

Microchipped.  Heartworm negative. Fully vaccinated and on heartworm prevention.

Out of state adoptions are welcome. However, fees are higher due to increased efforts to transport. Adoption fee $100. $150 transport fee for OUTSIDE of Texas  Health certificate $50 for OUTSIDE of Texas
