animal.description:
Meet Jimbo

Jimbo is about 5 years old and about 85. he's definitely a big boy! He came to us November 2019 from a shelter, where he was terrified and people could barely touch him.. we have come such a long way!! It took time and patience, but Jimbo will need someone who will is willing to be slow and patient with him, continuously showing him love and training that he needs. He does have separation anxiety, so it'd be so awesome if someone was able to be home with him, if not, he does well with blocking the door off because he wants to come with you. he's really good in the house, won't jump on the couch or get into things & lets you know when he has to go outside to potty. He gets so excited to see you that he actually SMILES!! its so adorable! He also has a best friend, his stuffed lamb. He takes her everywhere and can't live without her! Jimbo gives lots of kisses, so be ready once he's comfortable with you! cuddles not so much, every now and then he will surprise you! & he lovessss to be outside and get belly rubs! He will be your guard dog out there and let you know if he hears something but does not sit there and bark all the time. We are still working on the fact that people aren't something to fear- I think this is where the bad life came into play, he's still hesitant, in a fearful way, not aggressive, but it's a million times better! Fast movements are very scary for him, so no small children who won't understand how to properly move around him is best at this time as well, as he should be the only dog. He is on a joint supplement for his hips and will need that daily, so needless to say please don't expect him to be your hiking buddy or climb several flights of stairs everyday. He is up to date on all of his vaccinations and heartworm/ flea prevention. He does need a dental, which will be scheduled soon with the rescue so no worries about that and if he ever does need medicine, pill pockets with cheese are heaven LOL. Jimbo is the sweetest dog, has so much love to give and deserves the absolute best! Please let us know if you'd like to know more about Jimbo!!
If you are interested in adopting this dog please follow the link to fill out our application
https://toolkit.rescuegroups.org/of/f?c=SGVJMGQY

animal.description: Hi my name is Colby Jack. My friends, 117 of them to be exact, were rescued from a hoarding situation in the backwoods of Suwannee County Florida. In my prior living situation I lived outside together with over a hundred dogs in large pens. I am more comfortable with dogs than I am with people, but with the help of the nice people at the ranch I am learning to trust people. If possible, I would really benefit from another confident and relaxed dog in the home to help show me the way. I will do best with an experienced owner who understands what helping a dog transition into a loving home is. The good news is, is that of all my friends who have gone to their forever homes are doing very well and I am sure I will too if given the chance. Because I have already been through a lot and I need to learn to what it means to be loved I think it's best I go home to an adult only home.
animal.name: Colby Jack

animal.description: Hi! My name is Scooby! I have a huge amount of energy and am looking for a new family that wants a pup who can keep up with their busy lifestyle. I do like to socialize with other dogs here at the ranch (with proper introductions of course), but I would most certainly prefer to be the only dog in my new home. I'm still a young guy and my previous owner did not have time to properly train me to behave like a well mannered gentlemen, so any additional training would be welcomed. I love to hear the sound of my own voice and could you some help learning when it is ok to bark and when I should be a little quieter. I would love a yard to romp around in, so a free standing home as opposed to an apartment would make me happiest. I think I would be an excellent addition to any family and would most likely be a great lifetime partner for your little ones. But the most important thing to know about me is that I love people more than anything and I just can't wait to be part of your family.

animal.description: Hi! My name is Doralee! I was rescued from a high kill shelter by Big Dog Ranch just in time to give me a second chance. I am a sweet and charming little girl with the most expressive face, so you're never wondering what I'm feeling or thinking! I love to meet new people and I am always craving human companionship. While I do love to be snuggled, pleas keep in mind that I am not a fan of being picked up and would rather not be carried. My ideal home would be with an adult-only family where I can be the only dog in the home and get all of the love and attention to myself. While I was Heartworm positive when I arrived at the ranch, I have been given the full treatment and am happy that the medical team has gotten me to be Heartworm negative. I would love a great big yard to run around in and roam and play with my new owners. I would make an excellent companion to any individual or couple and I can promise that if you give me all of your love, I will give you all of mine right back!

animal.description:
If you are interested in any of the dogs available at New Leash Rescue, you can reach out to the foster listed below for more information and then complete an adoption application which can be found at https://www.newleashrescue.org/adopt/policy.  Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com

Meet Baby!

Baby joined New Leash Rescue along with her seven puppies last spring. She came from a rural area in South Dakota where she lived outdoors under a person’s deck tucked away. All of her puppies found loving homes and Baby also found a family of her own but she was recently returned. 

There were newly developing allergies in the home and in addition, she kept escaping her home (she didn't have a fence) and wandering around town. Her family was really sad but realized it was in her best interest to send her back to the rescue so she can find a new home where she will be fulfilled and safe. 

Baby is about 60 pounds and between 2 and 3 years old. She lives in a foster home with three other big dogs and two kids (age 4 and 6). She loves attention from all people, the more the merrier. 

She also likes to play with her dog friends but can come on somewhat strong so we would prefer to find her a home with a playmate her size but another canine is not required. She would do just fine as the only dog in the home, too. No cats or small critters for her though. They are far too tempting and interesting.

Baby crates really well and is quiet while crated and has not had any potty accidents since she has been back in rescue. Her perfect new home would have a 5 or 6 ft fenced in yard for her to romp around in and explore. She also loves car rides and rides very well in the car with you. We really want to find Baby’s own forever home that can fulfill all her needs. 

She has quite a bit of energy so her new family needs to be committed to keeping her exercised and content as a busy herding breed. No apartments for this girl as she can be vocal when she hears noise outside of the home.

Adoption Fee: $350 + tax (no checks) 

Please reach out with any questions to foster mom Andrea @ 218 831 6520 or tunelotti@gmail.com. 

Please check with the foster if Baby would attend an upcoming adoption event. 

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. 

There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

animal.description:
Humane Society/SPCA of Nelson County - ALMOST HOME

29 Stagebridge Road, Lovingston, VA 22949

Phone: 434 263-7722
Email: pets@nelsonspca.org

IMPORTANT!!! PLEASE READ

Posted animals are physically located at the above address except when indicated with the following notations after the animal's name:

Animal Name (FC=initials) -- indicates the animal is living in Foster Care. To meet the animal, please contact the foster directly when contact information is provided; otherwise call the shelter at 434 263-7722.

Animal Name (COURTESY) - this animal is posted as a public courtesy using information provided by the owner. Our shelter does not own or guarantee the information provided by the owner to be complete and accurate. Also, adoption does not involve our shelter but is strictly between the adopter and the owner.

VERY FRIENDLY & ENERGETIC!!!UPDATE 1/19/21:
You don't know what you are missing! This dog wants to listen to your complaints and worries and to be-there when you need someone the most.

Diego's eyes beg you to consider loving him, and if you do, he will love you back tenfold. He is a 5-year-old Shepherd (mix) that weighs 60 pounds. He responds to the words: SIT, WAIT, LEAVE-IT, GET IT, BRING IT, DROP IT, OFF, TAKE IT, and TOUCH IT. He loves pleasing the people he knows and whoever is fortunate enough to adopt him will quickly learn that Diego is waiting to live and die for you. (His estimated DOB is June 2015.)
One of his greatest joys is playing ball with someone he loves. He can catch a ball for an hour without getting bored, afterwards he'll cool off in any body of water he finds. He loves spending time outside exploring our big fenced yards. He thinks going for car a ride anytime to anywhere is a great thing to do. But at the end of the day, he really enjoys just relaxing on a soft spot in an air conditioned or comfortable room. He is clean in his environment and has proven to be house trained with good manners, in a home he recently stayed in for a couple of weeks. He also enjoyed their fenced back yard and did not try to dig or climb out. Unfortunately, the people were not equipped to adopt him.
Diego has spent time at the facility of one of our trainers (Denise), playing in her big yards with other dogs. We learned, if there is another dog in Diego's family, he would do best with a dog his size that does not try to push him around. Diego is very happy to have canine companionship, but it has to be the RIGHT dog. He knows how to take behavior cues from other dogs. That said, Diego can be too much for some dogs, so he would not be a good candidate to take to dog parks. Planned play dates with compatible dogs would be best.
Diego spent one wet day at an adoption event at Devils Backbone Basecamp. Dogs and people were all closely collected in the areas that had cover from the rain, and Diego was very well behaved. He loved the attention from people, and though he wanted very much to play with the other dogs and would yip and want to go up to sniff and say hi. He was still VERY good at listening to his handlers when told to leave it and settle down. He sat nicely to greet people and wagged his tail with happiness . He regularly enjoyed jogging around the perimeter of the site with his human buddy to catch a tennis ball and play in puddles. He didn't pull or try to get away as he sniffed, trotted about, and caught his ball. He had quite the fan club among venue guests but no compatible households for him.
Diego is a perfect match for ACTIVE adopters who can give him regular exercise, mental stimulation, and put in a little time to establish boundaries and reinforce his manners. He will love to join his owners on hikes or other outdoor activities. Diego has a great foundation of obedience and manners that should transition well into a home. He needs an owner who will enable him to be his best self by commitment to follow through with his training. He loves balls, toys water and people. He's just a great all-around guy.
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting Diego, contact Denise at info@campmerricks.com. She can set up a meeting away from the shelter. Diego is selective about the dogs he likes. He is not good with cats and is too much dog for children under 12. If you have the right home for Diego, he will keep you smiling, help you keep your body toned, make you feel safe, will listen to all your complaints, will try and do anything you ask, will lie at your feet, will keep you company on car drives, an most of all will love you more than you can fantasize.
VOLUNTEERS and DONATIONS NEEDED. Visit our website for more info: http://nelsonspca.org

animal.description:
Holly is around two years old, 60 lbs, came to us originally as a stray never reclaimed. Maybe a Husky/Pyrenees/Lab mix? She is an incredibly sweet dog, little shy at first, doesn't know what a leash or toys are about. Loves a tummy rub and getting attention. Her adopter that brought her back said she was not doing good with their male dog. She generally does well with a male dog buddy but is NOT good with other female dogs. She is an active girl so needs an equally active owner.
The first step to do an adoption is to do our Adoption Application here: https://www.elmorehumane.org/adoption-application-online-form2.html
ADOPTION FEES Dogs & Puppies.....$100.00. This Adoption fee includes: mandatory spay/neuter which will be done before you can take your dog or puppy home with you; basic canine immunizations (DHPP-CPV & Bordatella Intranasal); de-wormings; one-year rabies vaccination if old enough; heartworm test if over five months old; microchip from 24-Pet Watch; certificate for free health examination at your participating veterinarian; and a goodie bag chocked full of information, toys, and more.
Yes, there are sometimes exceptions to our normal fee for older dogs or special cases or adoptions of two dogs together. Some of our pets have also been lovingly sponsored by caring people and we will let the approved adopter know about that at the point of adoption. Visit our Website at: http://www.elmorehumane.org The staff would also like to remind you that for faster response to inquiries about adoptable animals to have the animals ID#, name & description.This way your questions will be answered in a timely manner.
You can also expedite the adoption process by filling our Adoption Application which you can find at: http://www.elmorehumane.org/HSEC_FORMS/AdoptionApplication.pdf and sending to us either by scanning and emailing to hselco@bellsouth.net or faxing to 334-567-8774.
All pet adoption websites & our shelter management software require that we choose a primary and/or secondary breed for our dogs. While our staff is quite breed knowledgeable, in many cases we are truly making our best guesses as to their breed(s) based on many factors but cannot promise that what we have said is accurate. So taking into account your own parameters for things such as size, coat care, activity level, etc please come and get to know our dog(s) as individuals to see if their personalities and yours are a forever match.
Thank you! Phone: (334) 567-3377 Fax: (334) 567-8774 E-mail: hselco@bellsouth.net 2/2/21 5:21 PM

animal.description:
WHOOF! WHOOF! WE'RE BOBBY & DYLAN, A SUPER SWEET, BONDED PAIR LOOKING FOR OUR OWN FAMILY, A LOVING FOREVER HOME TOGETHER. About 2 years old and 55lbs, we look like a mix of Aussie shepherd, labrador retriever and something with lots of freckles, maybe a pointer or springer spaniel. We have been in foster care for a while and are so ready to find our own home. Our guardian shares the following:

"I love this adorable duo! When Bobby & Dylan first came to us they were extremely shy, untrusting and skittish pups. It has taken some time for them to get comfortable enough with us for their awesome personalities to emerge. Bobby (aka freckles) is adventurous and curious so he responds fairly quickly to a patient, calm and loving guardian. He'll begin by following you around as you go about your daily activities. Dylan follows Bobby while keeping his eye on you. Initially Dylan is very much a wallflower and he needs more time to decompress and begin to feel that he is safe in this new home with this new person. If all goes well and life remains fairly calm and uneventful, within a few weeks Bobby should start letting his guard down. Just be calm and patient and give them time and lots of tasty treat bits and slowly, they will reveal their loving, affectionate, funny, playful and adorable personalities. They are highly treat motivated so we spend lots of hours sitting in a comfy chair and tossing yummie tidbits of high value lamb and sweet potato jerky treats to them. This may possibly be the key to their hearts.

Bobby and Dylan are very smart, crate trained, housebroken (initially Bobby needs to be watched for marking) and we are working on new commands and good leash and house manners. They enjoy boisterous playing with one another and several of my pups in the yard. They love any game that involves treats. Check out Mental Enrichment Activities or Boredom Busting Games on Barkercise.com. Enrichment toys like puzzle treats, snuffle rugs and activities like hide and seek, find the treat, where's the ball, etc., help immensely with confidence building and bonding.

They need slow introductions to new people, places and things. Ongoing training and confidence building exercises will be a must to help them be their best self. They enjoy playing with other friendly dogs but shy away from bossy pups. Their are several simple precautions that you must take to keep them safe. They need a home with a yard to run and play and secured by a 6' fence. We don't recommend you take them on walks outside the fenced in yard until they have fully bonded with you. When you do take them on walks, choose quiet places that aren't highly used to keep it calm. Always us quality, escape resistant harnesses and leashes to keep them secure.

Bobby & Dylan have stolen our hearts.... they are two of the most precious pups we've fostered in the last 4 years. They need a little extra help to overcome some of their issues from living on their own in a scary world but they are so worth it! In the first few days, they will steal your heart with gorgeous looks, puppy eyes, endearing expressions, and shy ways. As the days and weeks go by and they start sharing their sweet, silly and loving side with you, you will feel so special that these gorgeous creatures are beginning to appreciate, trust and love you....they've chosen you to be their hero.''

BOBBY & DYLAN are neutered and up to date on age appropriate vaccines. Adoption fee: let's talk! Please note that training is highly recommended for all dogs. As with all rescue animals, breed determination cannot be validated without genetic testing. Thanks for adopting and saving a life -- you are BOBBY & DYLAN's hero.

animal.description:
Hi!  My name is Milo.  I'm a handsome young dalmatian mix male about 2 yrs old who ended up in the LA City East Valley shelter in Van Nuys.  Luckily, Rescue saw me and made sure i  got out of there  quick. whew!   I am a shy boy, good with other dogs but wary of  strangers.  I will be learning  my leash manners now and  with the daily walking I should become less shy and more self confident in no time.  I am small and thin, only  38  lbs  when i got out of the shelter, but i know i'll be  eating well now!   Rescue thinks I cannot hear and that would be consistent with my breed and my very white coat, that would also explain why i am skiddish.   Because I am so shy and probably am deaf i would be best in a home with another dog or two and no young kids.  I am neutered, vaccinated  and microchipped so I am ready to go home anytime.   I have not had a good life so far but i would so love to have a new home and family to love.    Could  it be yours?

If you are  interested in meeting me, please contact Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc. by email at  dalrescue@sbcglobal.net .  To make sure  I would be a good  fit for you and your family, Rescue  asks that you complete an adoption  application, but once submitted and  approved,  arrangements  can be  quickly  made for  you to come meet me.   I would love to meet  you so please  email Rescue  and ask about me, Milo, Thanks!

To learn more  about Dalmatian Rescue of Southern California, Inc., please see our website   at www.dalrescuesocal.com.  You can also visit  us on facebook at www.facebook.com/spottyfriends.  We love seeing posts  and photos of life  with  your spotty friends  so please, keep them  coming.   Thanks!

animal.description:
#704 - Spryte | ACCEPTING APPLICATIONS

Hi! I'm Spryte, named after the mythical folklore creatures and their playful nature! I am a little over a year, fun, full of energy and will keep you on your toes! I am what my Foster Mom calls a "Border Whippet" which explains my size and stature. Female, spayed, house trained, crate trained (but I need a strong one as I can find a way to get out of those wimpy wire crates...). Other dogs are fun, especially if they like to move FAST. I've been known to outrun them and then jump over them as they get close. Did I mention I am a jumping bean and can flat jump over 5'? I'll need a tall fence to keep me contained. At night I like to sleep on my FM's feet when she watches TV, and sleep on the bed, always where I can snuggle up. I love belly rubs and ear scratches. I like to wrestle with the other foster dogs, and am too cute with I'm doing the bitey-face thing.

Spryte will need an active home. She does well with older children, she can knock over little ones when she jumps, hugs and kisses. She is not good with cats or other small animals… too much sight hound. She does love to run, and would make a good running buddy. She would be an awesome sport dog with some training. Foster home has been working on the basics like house breaking, crate training, socialization, barking, jumping. She will need continued leash training and will excel in a manners class. She likes to work with a clicker and food. She is active, fun and quirky and smart.

Meet Bruno!
This sweet boy was found at the Save A Pet gates early on Thanksgiving morning of 2019. We fell in love with him immediately and named him Spud! He was adopted from Save A Pet rather quickly and named Bruno... However, he was returned back after the adopter's living situation changed. They were unable to keep him.
Bruno loves playing with his best buddy Duke! Bruno and Duke run around and play all day. Bruno's very favorite thing is water!!! He LOVESSSSS to play in the water hose- he tries to eat the water and will play forever if allowed. It's quite comical to watch!
Bruno would do best in a home with older children and not a lot of commotion/visitors coming and going. We have discovered that Bruno is not a very confident puppy and needs some stability and training that will build his confidence and make him a more well-rounded dog.
Bruno does not make a mess in his kennel as he did great with house training and should be easy to re-acclimate back into a home setting!
If you would like more Information about Bruno, please call the Save A Pet shelter at 478-994-3882.

animal.description:
Daniel T. is a distinguished 14-year-old male German Shepherd Dog (GSD) that was owner surrendered to the shelter. The shelter volunteers advised that even at 14 years old he still knows how to have fun. He tries to enjoy each day as much as possible which could involve an activity as simple as enjoying a wonderful sunbathing session. He was affectionately referred to as their cute grandpa dog by one shelter volunteer. He is not the dog you would go running with or take on extended walks but he would enjoy short meanders in the neighborhood and he definitely will fill your home with his abundant affection.
 
Daniel T. Summary:
- Daniel is a Male, 14 yrs old, weighs 105lbs, current on shots, house-trained
- Good with Adults, some other dogs, and travel in the car

As you can likely see from looking at his included video Daniel is very friendly with the other dogs in his shelter playgroup and he does limp a bit on his right rear leg, The shelter vets did take a set of XRAYs of Daniels hindquarters and did confirm that his limp was related to arthritis in his spine, hip and stifle (equivalent to the human knee). This condition is not uncommon in older GSDs and at the age of 14 Daniel seems to be doing quite well... especially without having the benefit of medications for this condition. Fortunately for Daniel, the shelter vet immediately addressed his condition and got him started on a canine NSAID that should ease the pain and inflammation of his arthritis. Undoubtedly, this will have a positive quality of life improvement for Daniel so that his sunbathing sessions will be even more sweeeeet! Medications like Meloxicam or similar NSAIDs are also quite inexpensive (~ 10 to 25 cents per day) although Daniel's adopter will not need to account for this cost. Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR) will cover Daniel's related medical costs for the rest of his life.

Even though Daniel is a mellow dog and would clearly pass the Thulani behavior tests he was evaluated to assure that he could be expected to be safe and do well in a family home. The behavior tests include a check to see if he will guard or protect food from people and a check to see if he will tolerate a full-body feel test that ends up touching most areas of his body (ears, snout, check of his teeth, lifting paws, gently pulling his tail, and much more...). Lastly, we always check to see if a dog can get along with other well-behaved dogs. Daniel did indeed pass these tests without any incidents and as you can see in his included video he does get along nicely with other well behaved dogs.

Daniel was rescued from a S. Cal Shelter and was transported to Thulani Central in N. Cal (headquarters for TSGSR) where he is setting in. Daniel was calm and quiet for the 6+ hour ride to Thulani Central. The trip was broken up with frequent rest stops along the way not only helping Daniel to take care of nature's call but also helping our volunteer transport drivers get a break. At 105 lbs Daniel did need the help of a folding ramp to get into one of our taller transport vehicles but seemed to do fine with our assistance showing him the way.

Please join us in welcoming Daniel T. to Thulani Central. We are still getting to know Daniel so we will be continuing to update his bio.

What's Next for Daniel T.:
Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR) will continue to see that Daniel is well cared for and receives all medical care needed for his well being while in our care. In addition, TSGSR is beginning a search for an adoptive home that will care for him for the rest of his life. Daniel will come to his new home with a supply of food, a cushy pad if wanted, and other goodies such as toys. 

Daniels medical expenses will be covered for the rest of his life by Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR)!

If you want to learn more about Daniel, or are possibly interested in providing an adoptive or foster home, please send us a message by clicking on the "Ask About Me" button. We will often get feedback or "updates" from a dog's foster home and as any updates become available they will be included here.

If you are reading about Daniel on Petfinder.com sometimes an available YouTube video is not listed. If this occurs you can still view the video by pasting its URL into a new browser window or tab.
Available Video URL(s): https://youtu.be/a4mbo02AlcE

Saving one dog wont change the world. It will change the world for that one dog.

Good with dogs:  yes if low key and give Scrappy his space
Good with cats:  unsure
Good with kids:  unsure
Energy level:  unsure
Good with men/strangers:  yes but fearful of men
Hypoallergenic:  no

Special home requirements or medical:  Adult only home, no apts, , yard is a huge plus.

Additional info:

Scrappy Doo needs a patient adult only home (no apartments).   Having a yard is a huge plus. Scrappy's  leash aggression has improved.   It does take Scrappy some time to warm up to new people but once he trusts you he’ll want to give endless kisses and cuddles. 

Scrappy is fearful of men, so it may be best that he be in a home without any men. He tends to gravitate more toward women if given the choice, so if he placed in a home with both men and women he will have a hard time opening up to the man in the home so if this is the case they need to be prepared to put in some work to help him trust.

Because he is still struggling with some social skills, Scrappy needs to be in a calm environment that does not have a lot of visitors to the home. He can be a bit a bit of an alert barker when hearing unfamiliar noises so may not be suitable for apt living.

Scrappy Doo has come a long way but still will require a very special person that will understand his needs and continue to work with him every day. Scrappy is house trained and crate trained. He still needs to be kept safe and secure. He can be a little reactive to some people but, with continued work to help build his confidence, we know that will improve.

If you are not ready to adopt just yet and would like to help in other ways, please consider clicking on the green “Sponsor Me” button above to help this dog receive the best care we can give. We rely on the generosity of others to make rescuing dogs possible.

1.       Visit www.dogswithoutborders.org

animal.description:
Meet Betty! She was surrendered to an Oklahoma shelter in early 2019 in rough shape. She was only 30 pounds, depressed, and had lost all hope in humans. She is a Boxer/American Staffordshire Terrier mix. At her surrender, every bone in her body was visible. It was apparent that in addition to starving, humans had not been very kind to her. Betty took her freedom ride on February 2, 2019. Quickly after arriving in her foster home, it was discovered Betty had a severe case of heartworms, to the point she was coughing up blood. The first order of business was to get her healthy. She had to gain weight before she could even get vaccinations, let alone start invasive heartworm treatment. :( Thankfully, her amazing foster mom was able to keep her stable while she gained enough weight to be medically treated. 

Unfortunately she still has some psychological issues due to the complete lack of care she previously received from humans. ;( Medically speaking, though, she is completely healthy! She is up to date on age appropriate vaccinations and preventatives, spayed, micro-chipped, and heartworm NEGATIVE!!!! We are looking for a very special, understanding forever home for this incredible girl! 

She knows basic commands, is very treat motivated, and is a pleaser, which makes her very easy to train! She is house trained and leash trained. She spends most of her time in a kennel, since she does not get along with other animals but she does not mind too much, it's her safe space and she has always done really well in the kennel. She actually seems to love spending time in her kennel, where she can relax and decompress after a stressful day (which is basically every day for this sweet girl, since interactions with most living creatures are not her favorite thing). 

Betty is not great with humans, especially men. When her foster mom takes her to walk at the park, she is very reactive to men in general, but it's worse with men who have beards. Upon meeting any new person, she needs to be given time to explore them and get comfortable on her own. She cannot be petted immediately upon meeting someone. She will take a treat from new people, but then she sits back and watches them as if she is trying to figure out if they are good or not. She also does not like for most people to reach over top of her. She has never reacted to anything her foster mom has done, from picking her up, reaching over her, grinding her nails, giving her a bath, but with people she does not know, she will give a warning growl. She has never escalated to a bite since being in her foster home, but that could be because once she growls, her foster mom immediately removes her from the situation. She seems curious about kids, but has not been around them and would do best in a home without young children, possibly without children at all. The main reason for this is that children typically won't understand her background and how to interact appropriately with her! 

Betty also does not do well with other animals. Her foster home has cats and dogs of different sizes and temperaments, all of which she was reactive to. She has worked with a trainer and in that process met several dogs. It is easy to see her focus in before she reacts to another dog, and she is easily redirected. She seems to be able to relax and ignore non-dominant, SUPER laid-back dogs, but she should not go to a home with any other animals. 

As with many of our misfits, we will never know Betty’s whole story. She was spayed at some point before she wound up abandoned, neglected, and completely broken in a scary kennel environment. The heartbreaking part is that it is glaringly obvious that humans have not been kind to her. 

Betty LOVES chewing on bones, playing fetch and going for a walk at the park. She is not a high energy dog, but she does enjoy a walk around the block or a trip to the park. She will play fetch for hours and when inside, she just wants to be close to her foster mom, chewing on a bone. Betty has her issues (would she truly be a misfit if she didn't?!), but she is just a dog who has had a rough start in life and wants to be loved. 

Betty is safe, loved and seemingly happy with her life in her foster home. But if there is any chance that we can find her a perfect home where she doesn’t have to live in a kennel, she would be even happier (she just doesn’t realize it yet). 

Apply to meet / adopt her at www.muttmisfits.com/adoption-application

Albert is a handsome 5 year old Hound mix that can't wait to find his furever home! He loves attention and cuddling. Albert gets along with kids, other dogs, and cats. He really is the total package! 

Albert was picked up as a stray and was skin and bones, had a degloved lip, and had been shot in the leg. To save Albert's leg it was put in a splint for two months. animal.description:
Jake is a 4 year old Dalmatian / Lab Mix! Yes, Dalmatian! We have the DNA test to prove it! He’s sweet, fun-spirited and will greet you with a smile… really…. he shows you his teeth and flashes a winning smile! He is potty-trained & crate-trained and is a great listener. He loves to run in the backyard and chase squirrels and enjoys daily walks.

Jake will require some leash training and patience to be better on the leash and will need some barrier reactivity training. Since he was once a stray, he is extremely food driven; he will bark and insist on his feedings, and when eating, he inhales… but he will sit for his food. Jake has been wonderful with two female boxers but has had issues with other male dogs. It’s my recommendation Jake be the only dog in the household. Super friendly, loves cuddling and would be a wonderful addition to any family that wants a loyal companion to love! 

If you feel your home might be the right place for this wonderful dog, the place to start is with the adoption application found at www.dfwrescueme.org/adopt.  Once submitted, the foster will contact you to tell you more, and to arrange a meeting! The adoption fee for all of our dogs is $250.00, which includes their vaccinations and spay/neuter.

Jake is participating in the DFW Rescue Me Guest Dog Program, so custody and ongoing care are provided by the foster, not by DFWRM.

animal.description:
Born 10/27/2018, Hubert is an absolutely ADORABLE Chihuahua and Schnauzer mix. Just prior to his antipated eligible adoption date, Hubert was diagnosed with a significant pulmonic hypertension (January, 2019). A follow-up echocardiogram was completed in April, 2019, that recorded regular heart rhythm, no murmurs or gallops. The working status of Hubert's heart signficantly improved with his growth (it is not believed that Hubert will require surgery), but he is noted as having continued hypertension attributed to an underloaded left ventricle. He shows no signs of heart failure at this time and thus, the recommendation for Hubert's continued health will include (only) daily medication at this time, cost of which is approximately $85 per month). 

Hubert is a kindly and loving dog with an affectionate disposition. He loves people and plays well with children and other canine companions. Due to the status of his heart, a quiter home without crazy activity is thought to be best for Hubert's long-term health needs.

Our rescue is happy to share the findings of his echocardiogram results with any prospective adoptive family so that additional consulations can be made as needed. But please don't let a genetic abnormality prevent you from considering the adoption of this amazing dog, whom is as beautiful on the inside as he is on the outside!

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

NOTE: WE ONLY ADOPT TO SOME PARTS OF ONTARIO & QUEBEC, CANADA
*As far away as Barrie and Cambridge, Ontario & as far away as the Gatineau, Quebec area*
**NO Exceptions**
***We have ZERO control how Petfinder promotes the pets via their platform & sometimes our dogs show up in searches by people in the USA***

BHRR's Miss Lilly (DEAF & VISUALLY IMPAIRED) - female - Great Dane -~2 years of age, utd on vaccines, microchipped, good with other dogs & good with people, unknown with cats yet, integration is always key! Has had some obedience(this does not exclude our mandatory adoption clause of a full round of obedience being required - NO EXCEPTIONS!)

To read more about BHRR's Lilly and to stay updated on her progress, please follow her blog at http://www.birchhaven.org/archives/category/adoption/lily - CUT & PASTE the link into your browser. Petfinder no longer allows for html links.

NOTE: All blogs(scroll to the very bottom and then read upwards) and our PetFinder animal lists are kept utd so yes, BHRR's Lilly is still available.

Please do not EMAIL asking such and, please do go to her blog to read about her before contacting us. Almost all of your questions will be answered in her very detailed blog. READ the blog from the bottom up once on the blog.

Please familiarize yourself with BHRR's adoption mandates, processes plus policies before contacting us about a BHRR animal.

Our PetFinder and our www.birchhaven.org websites will answer most of your questions. Therefore, do not contact us asking us what our policies are,or what our adoption area is or what her adoption fee is. BHRR is a federally registered NPO operated solely by Volunteers. We are NOT a shelter or a pound.

You CANNOT just drop by to visit her. She resides in a loving home, not a kennel and BHRR has a thorough adoption process to determine if any home is a right match personality fit.

When submitting your adoption application contract for BHRR's Lilly; please also include a short introduction re: your home etc.

We DO NOT respond to inquires to adopt nor any emails that do not include an application along with the non-refundable application fee.

NOTE: WE also will not respond to any emails that only ask a one liner re: adoption fees. The adoption cost(from a r/q Rescue) or purchase cost(if you purchase from a reputable/quality Breeder is the LEAST that you shall pay over the lifetime of proper care of your pet).

animal.description:
ROLLIE is a one and a half year old mix of puppy love and rambunctious energy. ROLLIE is a strong, compact dude who knows basic commands but needs a strong leader who has breed experience who is willing to work with him and continue his 'good manners' training. His foster mom will be happy to explain her training techniques and work with his adoptive family to ensure a good adoption transition. ROLLIE can jump a 6 foot fence if left unattended, so he will require outdoor supervision and will do best in an active home with adults or older children (teens). He is simply too rambunctious for small kiddos. ROLLIE would love a family who will take him hiking or engage him in a game of fetch or even treat him to supervised swimming... this is his idea of time well spent! He would do best as an only dog as he really just gets a bit wound up in the company of other dogs:) Due to his activity level, an apartment or condo will not work, he needs room to run!

ROLLIE is full grown, a true wiggle-butt, who weighs about 35 lbs. He has been neutered, vaccinated and microchipped and is just waiting for his own forever home. If it is with you, please complete our online application at www.helpadogsmile.org. Please note, we do home visits prior to adoptions, so local Phoenix area adoptions only!

ROLLIE's adoption fee of $200 helps with medical expenses of the rescue.

Cilla

Located in the Sidney NE area
3ish years old
Blue Lacy mix
Is dog friendly with confident dogs
Not sure on cats
Great with kids
House trained
Kennel trained and knows a couple of commands
Fully vetted and ready to rock
45lbs

This sweet girl is Cilla and a few weeks ago she whelped an amazing litter of 12 and was the most fantastic momma. She was saved by another private rescuer who didn't realize she was pregnant, at that point she reached out for help as it was beyond her abilities. We were happy to help and Cilla settled in without missing a step. After she whelped and weaned her pups she did have an incident while playing with a small dog and others in the yard but we do not know what happened, the dog was severely injured. She also needs to be in a home with other confident dogs. Cilla did amazing with all of the fosters dogs except 1, that dog was very nervous and unsure. This girl is crate trained, house trained, likes to swim, loves kids, well loves people in general and is good with most dogs.

If interested in helping Cilla please contact us!
To Contact Us
Message us through our website http://www.highplainspaw.org
Message the Facebook Page at https://www.facebook.com/HighPlainsPAW Fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/adoption-application Fill out our Foster Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/foster-application Email us at highplainspaw@gmail.com
Call our voicemail at (402)957-1578

 $200.00 Adoption Fee
(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY ALL OUR DOGS ARE LOCATED IN FOSTER HOMES. This means there is no place for you to go in person to view our dogs. We ask that an application be filled out and we will go from there!

animal.description:
Gizmo was as sad as any dog we have brought into rescue when he came. He
was at our vet clinic for weeks and several times we weren't sure he would pull
through, took him almost a week to raise his head when it was time to interact;
and a couple of weeks before he would make eye contact. 

Someone had chopped his ears off and he presented as a bait dog, emaciated, scarred and emotionally shut down.

Hard to believe he's the same loving, outgoing dog he is today. Attention and
food are his favorite two things. He gets along w/most of the other dogs in his
foster home except when it's time for attention and then he wants it all for
himself. He has regained his appetite for food and for fun - he loves to be part of
whatever is going on with his family.

Gizmo is crate trained although he's not a fan of the crate and he has good
house manners but if he has to go he usually needs to go right away so his
family will need to be aware when he's asking to go out.

He would be OK in a home with another dog as long as they get along initially but
he has met a couple of guys he just doesn't like. He would be fine as an only
furkid and enjoy having his humans all to himself.

Gizmo is on an anti-inflammatory and thyroid medication full time to keep his
healthy and active. He's great about taking his meds and neither is very
expensive. He's active, healthy, and ready for his forever home. This guy will
give back all the love and devotion any dog could possibly bring to their home.
animal.name: Gizmo

animal.description:
We cover Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, Kentucky, Missouri, Nebraska, Oklahoma and Wisconsin and transportation is available for adoptions within those states. Otto is currently in Iowa. 
This big handsome hunk is Otto. Otto is a special guy. 

Otto has been through some things in his 5 years. Some good, and some bad. Otto has a little baggage from all that but hes ready to live the next 5 years of his life in a much different way!

Hes a big guy, and still needs to lose a few pounds. Hey, he likes his cookies. But he also loves playing in the yard, fetch, and walks, so it should be easy to help him get his summer body ready. He also likes to play with other dogs that are medium to large size. Hes okay with smaller dogs too, as long as they dont pester him too much. Hes pretty good at knowing when to leave another dog alone if that dog is a fun hater. Otto enjoys going for walks, and does pretty well on a leash, although he occasionally tries to chase loud vehicles. We walk him in a Halti, and its easy to redirect him if he does try to do that. 

Otto likes his person. Hes okay with other people, too, after getting a chance to check them out and they take the time to let him get used to them being around. But once he trusts you you are HIS PERSON. He will seek you out, and respect you, and want to do what you are doing. He will sit in your lap and wait for you to scratch his booty and his back. It would be advantageous if his forever person had some experience with large, stubborn, handsome dogs, and can be a strong, confident leader for Otto.

When Otto likes something, he REALLY LIKES IT. So occasionally, he will feel the need to guard the things he likesyouhis ballhis foodhis space. From others. So if you are meant to be Ottos person, you will need to be watchful of that and be ready to offer him a better deal- hot dog pieces are always effective- to change his mind. For this reason, although Otto does like kids, older kids who can help him disengage from this behavior if needed would be the best fit, if his person has a family. His foster mom does not have any issues with changing his mind, all it takes is a stern NO, and a change of scenery. 

This guy thrives on structure and boundaries. Although he is very well behaved in the house and is perfectly potty trained and does not chew things that are not meant to be chewed, he can get a bit big for his britches if he does not have some boundaries. Some kennel time is great for this, and his foster mom has him earn every last bit of food or treats he gets with obedience and trick cues. Otto enjoys being able to give the right answers to get his rewards! Otto also needs TIME to learn to trust new people. Otto's potential adopter must be willing to take it VERY SLOW with handling. Otto can be very defensive of his head and neck area at first. His first couple of weeks MUST be dedicated to decompression, and we highly recommend that he wear a leash during that time for low-pressure handling as he learns to trust his new person.

Ottos perfect forever home might look like this another middle-aged dog who likes to play occasionally, but knows when enough is enough a yard with a deck or sunny spot to nap on when the weather is good, or a person who enjoys medium-length walks a couple times a day a person who can give him structure and boundaries- not prison style (you will sit in one spot all day and eat slop for dinner), but more like grade-school style (no Johnny, you may not sit on the teachers desk or write bad words on the board. No Suzie, you cannot eat the lunch of the girl sitting next to you while shes looking the other way). Otto would like a home that doesnt have too many visitors in and out, and when there are visitors, he has a chance to meet them on his own terms, in a polite way, of course. Hed love a couple games of fetch each day, and some booty and back scratches to finish things out. 

Remember that whole thing about Otto needing to be able to check people out on his own terms? Well, usually when he has to go see the vet, he cant do that. So for that reason, he is muzzle trained and can wear a muzzle for situations just such as that. His muzzle will accompany him to his forever home, like an old friend. 

So, hes not perfect! But then again, perfect is boring.
animal.name: Otto

animal.description:
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS
Fenced yard

My name is Nigel. I wandered up to a families farm one day and decided I liked it there. They weren't able to keep me so they called this nice rescue to see if they could help me find a mom. Because of a foster person, they said yes and here I am living the good life until I find my new family. I am a Shepherd/Husky mix. I am about 3 years old and weigh appx 65lbs. As you can see i love my toys. I am good with the female dogs that I have met and would probably be ok with laid back submissive males too. I don't share very well whether its my person or toys. It is believed that I was once a house dog because I am crate trained and I don't mind being in it as long as my stuff can be in it with her. I am housebroken also.Now if you meet my you might think something wrong with my leg. My rescue mom thought so too but the vet says it's fine and could possibly be an old injury. Doesn't bother me much so I hope it won't bother you either. 
If you would like to meet me send an email to theloveofk9s@yahoo.com. Please allow 24 hours for a reply.

Adoption donation pays for all vetting...my neuter, a heart worm test, all vaccinations, deworming, flea prevention and a wellness exam

Estimated at 5 1/2 months old, Gertrude and her sister and brother were found in a crate in the middle of an abandoned trailer park. She is being spayed on June 10th. She has been vaccinated and started on heartworm prevention.


Application: www.maxshope.com

Adoption fee: $85 including her spay 

Please include your veterinarian name, number and the name your current pets are listed under. Also please check your information carefully. All current pets must be up to date on vaccines and spayed/neutered. Dogs must be on heart worm preventative.
Adoption Process: This is not a first come, first serve organization. We will process applications within 48 business hours of receiving them. The application must be completed in full including first and last name, complete address including city and state, complete veterinarian information(this will be checked and all pets must be neutered or spayed, up to date on all vaccines, and dogs must be current on heartworm prevention) and the name of all current pets in the household. We are 100% volunteers and I will not subject anyone who is giving of themselves and their time to hostile conversations. Please be patient with us. We are not paid for our endless hours and are looking for the BEST home for the babies in our care.

We will process your information and an email will be sent to the email you provide on the application within 48 hours.

animal.description: McCloud has been our longest stay dog at the shelter to this point. He originally was surrendered to Plumas County Animal Control after spending a lot of times roaming the streets here in Portola. He was only here for a short stint initially before being adopted into a home. Unfortunately, it was not the right fit and owners, and McCloud was returned to us after some fearful interactions with strangers approaching him. Since he has returned we have been working with McCloud and he is now muzzle-trained so that he can go on walks and be less fearful of the strangers that he passes by. He is a dog that wants to please his owners and would be a very good dog for someone who is looking for a dog who likes to alert them when people approach the house. He gets along with other dogs, able to chase toys and let other dogs have them, but he can be a little guarded of his toys when they are in his possession (only from other dogs though). McCloud is looking for his forever home still and would love to show some humans how far along he has come in order to fit right into his family. If you are interested in meeting McCloud, please fill out an application on our website www.highsierraanimalrescue.org. We do not discuss any potential adoptions without an already submitted application.

animal.description:
Sassy came to us very pregnant after being dumped in a shelter here in Texas. All her babies have gone on to find homes except for scruffy jean (who is also listed for adoption).
 Sassy is around 30 lbs and about the size of a beagle...which we believe she is mixed with.  Her coat and a lot of her personality lean towards being a possible sharpei mix as well. 
Sassy and her daughter have very shy personalities when meeting new people.  They also do not love going to the vet or car rides. We really believe this is just a personality quirk as we know Scruffy Jean has never been abused and the other female puppies has similar traits as mamma. 
Sassy only "negative" trait is her shyness and while she can be fearful she is not aggressive.  She loves to play with other dogs and loves to be bossy but she is also so sweet and cuddly.... a lap baby who would love nothing more than a quiet home with maybe another dog for a play friend. 
Sassy is crate trained and actually really loves her kennel as it makes her feel safe and gives her comfort. She LOVES treats and bones of any kind.  She does do well on a leash and harness and with time and some patience we feel she may get used to going new places but would certainly like walks around the neighborhood to start. 
Because of her shyness, Sassy is only available to adopt to local homes near to Houston tx area.  Any adopters will need to meet her first in her own home environment as traveling and new places are currently scary for her. 
If you have any further questions or would like an application to adopt please don't hesitate to email us. 
Sassy deserves a home and family of her own where she can get all the love she craves.

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

319-372-2274

WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
Location: Colorado Springs, Colorado

Layla was a owner surrender to a shelter in Colorado. Cane Haven Rescue pulled her from the shelter to give her another chance at life. Layla is approximately 4 years old, up to date on vaccinations, spayed & microchipped. 

We do not know much about Layla's past except it was not a good one. She came into rescue with battle wounds that are slowly healing. Until Layla can trust again, we feel she would do best in a home with no other pets. One day when she knows she is safe, we would properly introduce her to other pets. Layla is a complete love bug. She loves belly rubs, playing outside & cuddling! 

Layla is house trained, kennel trained & knows her basic commands/manners. 

Interested adopters can fill out an application at canehavenrescue.com. 
Any possible questions about Layla, please email canehavenrescue@gmail.com 

Cane Haven Rescue will transport any of their adoptable dogs to the right home. We do require adoption fees that are based on the age & health status of the adoptable dog. The adoption fee covers every single dog in CHR with vaccinations, heartworm test, deworming, microchip, spay/neuter & medications. All CHR adoptable dogs are current on their monthly  heartworm and flea medication. A CHR representative will do a home check to ensure the pets are placed in a secure and loving home. 

www.canehavenrescue.com

animal.description:
Blackie keeps getting over looked because he’s a big black dog. He’s about a year old now, neutered, microchipped and weighs about 75 pounds. He takes treats so very gently and does know a few commands. He just doesn’t realize he is as big as he is. He gets so excited and really would love to have another four legged friend to romp around with. 
He was a stray in the Olive Branch area and needed help. He's doing well on leash and is mastering not jumping up on people.  He was on a farm and decided chickens were too much fun to chase.  That didn't work out too well for him. 
He would love to have a romping partner to play with.  He hasn't bothered any of the cats in his foster home.
Sadly, Blackie tested very light positive for heartworms and has now taken his 30 days of Doxycycline.  He is now on Advantage Multi to treat his heartworms with the slow kill method.  Hopefully he will test negative in the next 6-12 months with this treatment. 
His adoption fee is $150 and would include supplying the  Doxycycline and Advantage Multi for his treatment.

If you are interested in adopting, we encourage you to fill out our adoption questionnaire at http://members.petfinder.com/~MS72/adoption_app.html

Save 1 Pet is a 501 (c) 3 approved charity committed to helping homeless animals.  We don't have a facility (shelter) but work out of our homes to foster the animals until they find a forever home.

Please be advised that for all adoptions, we will conduct reference checks, including veterinary references.  Our adoption fee for dogs includes spay/neuter, heart worm check, current vaccines, microchip, worming and heart worm/flea/tick prevention.
For dog adoptions, we do conduct fence verification.
When adopting an animal, you will be asked to complete our Adoption Contract

JOEY HAS TESTED POSITIVE FOR HEART WORM AND IS BEING TREATED. HE WILL BE READY FOR ADOPTION IN JULY.

JOEY is a friendly, 1-year-old, 40-pound Hound mix. JOEY is playful, enthusiastic, and game for anything! He's got a lust for life and the power to infect everyone around him with the same! JOEY is a wonderful companion and would be a fantastic addition to any family! WHAT'S NEXT? If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY! Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date! *** This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives. Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. BY APPOINTMENT ONLY: Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins). An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals. Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please). This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times. Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details. To fill out an adoption application, go to: https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

animal.description:
I came to rescue after I wound up at animal services as a stray and one ever came to claim me. A nice volunteer with From The Heart offered to take me in to save my life. I am a sweet boy! I get along with other dogs too. I had a rough life before coming to rescue. I had mange AND heartworm AND erlichia! From The Heart made sure I received the vet care I needed to get better. With TLC and vet care I am now a happy healthy boy again! I also had a tumor removed! It looked a little funny so we had it sent off to be looked at in a lab. Turns out it was cancer! Luckily, the vet said they removed all of it! She said that there's a chance it could grow back again...or there's also a chance I'll never have another tumor ever again and will live a full life. She says that's life! You never know with these kinds of things...I'm feeling great now and living every moment to the fullest! I am such a happy thing! I'm feeling great and I'm doing well! I had a rough start in life. The heartworm unfortunately took it's toll on me. I have a small heart murmur from the damage they did inside my heart. So far it's not giving me any trouble. In fact, I don't even notice it! I am very photogenic and I'm such a smiley boy. I'm housebroken and walk great on a leash.l I love walks! My foster mom has even taught me how to sit. I'm very loyal and I can't wait to have a family all of my own! Fill out an adoption application to meet me! Learn more about me and fill out an online adoption application on the From the Heart Rescue website at: www.fthar.org.

My requested adoption donation includes my spay/neuter, age appropriate vaccinations and medical care to date, microchip implantation and registration, collar, leash, ID tag, health check-up and one month of free pet health insurance (some restrictions may apply).

If Im not exactly what you want, please visit my other friends in rescue at From The Heart Rescue on our website at www.fthar.org.

animal.description: Sweet Sarge dog Dixie was feeling terrible within a day or so of her arrival at the Adoption Center. Thankfully, Dr. Frankie at Haywood Animal Emergency was able to figure out the puzzling symptoms and diagnose Addison's disease. Her recovery was dramatic, literally overnight, and she is now a happy, lively wonderful young dog. Addison's disease (hypoadrenocorticism) is caused by a lower than normal production of hormones, such as cortisol, by the adrenal glands. Treatment requires a monthly injection to supplement the adrenal hormones. This makes her 'special needs' and perhaps difficult to place, We're hopeful that potential adopters will see beyond the Addison's, and recognize the wonderful, happy dog whose condition can be well controlled with medication. As far as her new home, we have not observed her behaving well with other dogs, so she would need to be the only dog in a new home.If you'd like to give Dixie a chance for a great life in your home, please complete the application on our website, www.sarges.org, and we'll contact you to set up an appointment for a meeting. 2/2/21 10:16 AM

animal.description:
Lexie has one obsession.....TOYS!  She loves her toys and will pull them all out of the toy box and play with them, one by one.  She carries them around the house and takes one on walks.  It is pretty adorable!  

Lexie has such a gorgeous tuxedo coat, is solid muscle and knows commands such as sit, down and shake, she is really just the sweetest.  

Lexie has not been around children but we believe with proper introduction and supervision, she would be fine with them.  She is an energetic girl so older children would probably be best.

Lexie has a very high prey drive and would do great as an only pet, so no pets or outdoor farm animals as she will chase them.  Lexie is working on her reactivity towards dogs when walking on a leash and is doing better but still needs some practice.   She is the cutest bumble bee we have ever seen!

Fun Facts:

Age (best guess) - 3-4 years
Breed (best guess) - Pitbul
Current Weight - 52 lbs
Dog Friendly - Very Selective, an only dog home is best
Cat Friendly - No
Kid Friendly - Unknown
Potty Trained - Yes
Crate Trained - Yes
Leash Trained - Yes

All of our adult dogs are current on vaccinations, de-wormed, heart worm tested, spayed/neutered, on monthly preventatives & micro chipped prior to adoption. 

*Adoption Fee is $200.00, No out of State Adoptions ,Virtual Home Visits 
 Required  

*We do not require fenced yards for all dogs, fenced yards are required based on a dogs needs. *No invisible fences.

If you would like to meet this dog, please fill out an adoption application at www.unchainedmelodies.org/adopt/

Thank you for adopting!

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
Maya von Malchin is a stunning 3.5 year old black-and-red German Shepherd on the smaller side. Her beautiful face and classic GSD looks will pull on your heartstrings. She loves people and enjoys playing with toys. Fetch is one of her favorite pastimes! Per her previous owners, Maya is housebroken, good with children, knows her commands like sit, stay and leave it, and was good in the home and yard. Maya walks well on a leash, but does get excited when she sees other dogs, so will do best with an owner who can continue her training. Once she has a chance to greet the other pups, she walks nicely in a group of dogs.  She seems more relaxed when she is off leash and has been well-behaved around dogs in playgroup (but she's a no for cats). Maya deserves a home where she can run freely with her toys and play fetch with her owner! She is ready and waiting to meet you, wherever you may be.
Maya needs a special diet for intestinal issues.

animal.description:
Rocco is a young German Shepherd boy, he is about two years old. He kisses you every chance he has and loves to cuddle! Rocco is very people-oriented: every time his foster family is watching TV together he tries to get as close as possible to them, observing them or just sleeping somewhere nearby.
Rocco was surrendered by his owner because he cannot walk well. He is underweight (56 pounds) and needs special care. We don't know the reason for his knee injuries but the good news is that with few medical procedures his life should dramatically improve!
Rocco will become a loving friend for a whole family: despite all the difficulties walking he still comes to you to cuddle.. Also he is very smart: Rocco learned "shake" in 10 minutes! He will be best in a family with no other pets because he is scared of other dogs. Dog behavior specialist is working with Rocco and the progress is really great so far, but he will still need some time and a patient family to overcome those issues.
Adoption Application: https://angelsfurryfriends.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Please note that while we are closed to the public we will not be responding to pet inquiries. Once animals are posted, we immediately begin receiving adoption applications. With one volunteer available to review all applications, we appreciate your patience as you wait for an email response. Adoption appointments are scheduled in the order that approved applications are received. You can find our adoption procedures and online application at warmhearts.org/adopt.

BREED RESTRICTIONS/SPECIAL ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS: Background and home check; must have completely enclosed/fenced yard; and no apartments. 

Jack is a handsome boy who came to us as a stray; therefore, we do not have any background information. Jack is great with humans but does not seem to care much for cats. He seems to do okay with some dogs. Jack's estimated DOB is 7/4/2019; he weighs approximately 60 pounds.

Jack was generously sponsored by Anh Thu Doan during our virtual Reigning Cats and Dogs event. Thank you Anh for sponsoring Jack!

HSPC's adoption fee is seventy-five-dollars through December 31, 2020, unless stated otherwise within the pet's description. At times, our adoption fees are lowered during special events that are posted to our website or Facebook page. Every pet that is available for adoption has been spayed/neutered, microchipped, and is up-to-date on vaccinations including heartworm preventative (canines). Adopters are required to schedule a wellness exam with their veterinarian at their cost within 7 days of adoption.

Please only submit one application. Once you are contacted by email, you will have an opportunity to provide us with any additional animal(s) under consideration.

animal.description:
Abby
#themylofoundation
Florida Gulf Coast / Alabama

We got a message today from a lady who seriously needs our help!! She has obviously been through so much already! We have to help her!!
The lady’s son found her about 2 weeks ago. They have been calling her Abby. She was dragging a broken rope that was knotted around her neck, the knot was under her chin and bigger than a baseball. Her son had to cut it off her. She looked so bad I couldn't stand it so I took her to the vet. The vet said those are chemical burns on her, God knows from what. She is being treated with antibiotics and some other kind medicine. She is 5 years old and 51 Pounds. She is very sweet and very excited to see people.
The vet said she did very good when they examined her besides being a wiggle butt. She needs to be with someone who will love her and show her attention. I doubt she's ever has any.
She is begging for a foster to save her and show her what true love means!!

Jotform.us/gcurgents/mylo

If you can’t foster, pledges save lives too!

animal.description:
Roscoe ~ Available...Roscoe is a handsome, fawn and white, male Shepherd mix. He is approximately 8 years old and weighs around 75 pounds. He has a low/moderate energy level and is crate-trained and housebroken.

While he may be an older boy, he is very athletic and loves to go for walks and hikes. He has a great balance of being active and ready for outings but is also very calm and relaxed while at home. He is good with older kids and is social with other dogs but has not been cat-tested. Because of his age, he is available for the reduced "senior" adoption fee and training fee (see details below).
For more information or to request an adoption application, please email us at adoption.mtgsr@gmail.com

ADOPTION: Training (for both the dog AND the family) increases the probability of a successful adoption. We feel strongly that training is an essential part of responsible dog ownership and we now require training for every dog placed through the MTGSR program.

Roscoe's total cost of adoption is $250 which includes the $125 senior adoption fee and a training fee (payable to the trainer) of $125 is due at the time of adoption.

For the adoption fee, the dog will be spayed/neutered, current on all vaccinations, current on heartworm/flea-tick preventatives and microchipped.

The training fee will include a plan tailored to that specific dog and that dog's needs (obedience training, behavior modification, etc.) and includes two private training sessions.

PLEASE NOTE: Our philosophy is "Rescue locally, place locally" which means we primarily pull dogs from shelters in the Nashville area AND we place dogs within a one-hour drive of Nashville. If you are outside of the Nashville area, please consider adopting a homeless dog in your local community.

animal.description:
Samson is less than 50lbs with a big personality. Samson lights up whenever his people enter the room, and begins to wiggle and jump excitedly. Samson has only been with the rescue a short time, but quickly showed what a happy, fun guy he is. He is progressing well with his basic deference training, and is able to sit politely to wait for his treat. Samson is not all that interested in fetch, and is content to enjoy his time exploring the yard.

Samson has a good recall and will come to the door promptly when he is called from his  enclosed privacy fence yard. Samson is also doing well with his leash training when he is on walks. He is just an overall happy guy who is waiting for the right family to come along to forever change their lives for the better.

Samson is a neutered, male and is approximately 2 years old (2020). Samson had his life saved thanks to a partner rescue stepping up to pull him the day he was set to be euthanized and care for him until MAPS was able to take Samson into their foster home program. 

Application Process

MAPS’s adoption process is designed to help best place dogs with homes that are in the best interest of the dog and their human companions. The adoption process starts with a prescreen review of a Guardian Application. Making decisions about dog placement in adoptive homes is an "art", not a "science", and there will be times when applications will be denied for various reason(s). This is left to the discretion of the MAPS after reviewing relevant information. MAPS reserves the right to make all decisions regarding placement or final disposition of any rescued dog in its care into a foster or adoptive home. There is absolutely no guarantee, made or implied, that any person or persons requesting to adopt a dog being fostered through MAPS, or posted on MAP's web site, will be granted an adoption. After a successful prescreen, including background checks, the applicant(s) are notified that they can visit the dogs and a time slot is made for the dog and applicant interaction. After the interaction we encourage several days of reflection before adopting a pet to help assure this will be a lifetime commitment of love and quality care for the dog. Next we conduct a home/neighborhood visit to the Guardian Applicant's home. If the home visit proves successful the new mom and/or dad of the dog will sign an Adoption Agreement and share a lifetime of love and mindful growth !

Guardianship Application available for download at

http://tinyurl.com/MAPSFiles

MAPS Dog Rescue Mission

Midwest Area Pit Stop, Inc. (MAPS) is a foster home based rescue located in Madison, Wisconsin established in 2005 after being part of the Chicago Illinois based rescue Furry Friends for several years. MAPS focuses on providing a structured, safe calm environment for the dogs in their care that helps them flourish. This structured home environment is complimented by exercise, Positive Reinforcement Deference Training, very high quality dog food in addition to a broad spectrum of proven food supplements including vitamins and supplements. In addition to fostering, MAPS provides sponsorship funds to help with the veterinary expenses and/or Breed DNA testing to save dogs in need of a rescue at the end of their options. MAPS has been active in the community promoting dog safety, how to build a healthy relationship with your dog, and fighting breed discrimination including breed testing of hundreds of dogs since December 2007. MAPS believes that dogs are a central component for people to have a more meaningful and purposeful life. That is, if people are willing to embrace mindfulness in daily living. Dogs help us connect to reality and make life worth living through example and deep bonds. MAPS is not about how many dogs are adopted in the shortest amount of time but rather measures to help insure the dogs that are adopted do not come back for the wrong reasons.
